<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-2 to UPDATE with jury deliberating three hours
before leaving.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> lied when they said <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> authorized them to take ministry money they used to buy property and jewelry, a prosecutor said Monday before deliberations began in the Taggarts' tax evasion trial. The jury started deliberations just after 5 p.m. on the 12th day of the trial. Jurors left after three hours and were to resume Tuesday. `` In a nutshell, this case is about power,'' prosecutor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said in his closing statement in the brothers' trial. `` The power <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> and his brother exercised at <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> to line their own pockets.'' The Taggarts are charged with evading $ 525,000 in income taxes after spending nearly $ 1.2 million in <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> money on personal luxuries such as condominums, jewelry, expensive cars and designer clothes. The trial began July 5. If convicted, each brother could be sentenced to 25 years in prison and face fines of more than $ 1 million. The defense rested Thursday following two days of testimony from the Taggarts, who began at <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> as piano players. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> gave no reasons for then postponing Friday's session Within a few years of joining <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> in the late 1970s, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON>, 32, was <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>'s top personal aide. <PERSON> James </PERSON>, 35, was the interior designer at <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> retreat just south of <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>. Before his closing remarks, defense attorney <PERSON> Ben </PERSON