<HEAD>Thatcher Names New Foreign, Defense Secretaries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Mrs. Thatcher...' to CORRECT title of social
security secretary.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> appointed new foreign and defense secretaries Monday, fired two Cabinet ministers and switched around others in the biggest government shake-up since she won power 10 years ago. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> named <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Major </PERSON>, one of the least-known members of her 22-member Cabinet, as the new foreign secretary, making him a prime contender to succeed her. He replaces Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, who was moved to a vacant post as deputy prime minister. <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> will also lead the governing <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>. The prime minister, battling to halt her government's slide in popularity, also put new appointees in an array of major posts including the portfolios for <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and the environment. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> fired her harassed <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON>, who had been accused of bungling bomb warnings before <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 was blown up over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> on Dec. 21, and Social Security Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. The two other Cabinet ministers to depart _ <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Younger </PERSON> and Trade and Industry Secretary Lord Young _ said they were resigning to resume business careers. Northern Ireland Secretary <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> was named defense secretary in an apparent reward after four years as <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s top official in the embattled province. The appointment of Major as foreign secretary was a big step up from his former <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> post as chief secretary to the treasury, the No. 2 financial official. The 46-year-old son of a circus trapeze artist was raised in poverty in south <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s rundown <LOCATION> Brixton </LOCATION> district, never went to university and worked as a building laborer before making a career in banking. He entered Parliament in the May 1979 general election that brought Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to power and ousted a socialist <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government. His appointment underlined the transformation of the hierarchy of the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, once the preserve of the British upper classes, since Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, a grocer's daughter, took over. `` We now know, without the need for guesswork, who her chosen successor will be,'' <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s liberal Guardian newspaper commented Tuesday. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, 63, is widely expected to retire some time after bidding for an unprecedented fourth successive term at the next election. It must be held by mid-1992. The move of <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, 62, to deputy prime minister was widely regarded as a demotion from one of the most prestigious jobs in the Cabinet. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> also brought into the Cabinet another member of the class of 1979, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Patten </PERSON>, a rising star from the party's liberal wing, as the new environment secretary. Reflecting anxiety at the government's drop in the polls and its drubbing in elections for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> last month, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> shifted Education Secretary <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> to the chairmanship of the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Party chairman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON> was named <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> Secretary, a tough job that effectively removes the incumbent from day-to-day contact with party political issues in mainland <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Energy Secretary <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkinson </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> favorite whose political career was interrupted after a scandal over an extramarital liaison six years ago, was named transport secretary. He resigned from the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 after news broke that his ex-secretary, with whom he had an affair, was carrying his child. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> brought him back into the Cabinet when she won a third term in May 1987. The shake-up, announced after Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> summoned government ministers to her Downing Street office for private meetings, appeared aimed primarily at freshening the government's image. Beset by rising inflation, a revival of labor union militancy and facing a much tougher challenge from the revived <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has trailed <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> seven to 15 points in polls since the spring. <PERSON> Patten </PERSON> succeeded <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>, a chain-smoking scion of an aristocratic family, who was named trade and industry secretary. <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>, accused by critics of mishandling the current passage through Parliament of a controversial new tax, is deeply unpopular with many party members, who blame him for worsening the government's poll standing. But Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who has the sole power to appoint <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ministers, has repeatedly defended him. The dismissal of <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Channon </PERSON>, an heir to the Guinness brewing fortune and reputedly the richest member of the Cabinet, had been predicted. In the aftermath of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> disaster, his department was accused of being tardy about passing on detailed bomb warnings to airlines. Critics also said he mishandled current strikes by employees of <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Underground. Other new Cabinet appointments announced were <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamont </PERSON> as treasury secretary and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gummer </PERSON> as Agriculture Minister. Both previously held government jobs outside the Cabinet. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakeham </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader in the Commons, became the new energy secretary, and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>, former trade minister, the new social security secretary.
