<SECOND>PM-Bush Bounces Back, Bjt,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush a `Late Bloomer'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, rebounding from negative reviews early in his presidency, is now winning good marks after two successful trips to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and a general sense of economic well-being at home. The president is `` a late bloomer,'' says one analyst. At the 100-day point, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was criticized as being too cautious, unimaginative and unwilling to compete with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. After six months in office, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> basks in praise for winning support at a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan to reduce conventional arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and for traveling to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to encourage democratic reforms. `` He's actually done well after a halting beginning,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON>, a presidential scholar at <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was `` aided enormously by the fact that the Democrats in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> were in disarray'' as House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Whip <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> struggled with ethical problems and then resigned. `` There was no challenge to his leadership.'' After losing a battle with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for confirmation of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> as secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> came back with a decisive victory on his veto of a $ 1.20 increase in the minimum wage. `` He's obviously in a lot better shape than he was at 100 days,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON>, a presidential scholar at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>. `` He's had two awfully good trips abroad and when a president travels abroad, he gets an awful lot of attention.'' <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> political scientist who called <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a late bloomer, said, `` It's as though there's a second honeymoon at the six-month point. `` It's tied to real successes, particularly in the foreign sphere, and things are going reasonably well abroad and at home,'' <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON> said. `` The economy may be slow but it's not in recession. There's no war or threat of it, and things appear to be going in our direction.'' <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON>, a political analyst at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s foreign travels `` tilt the balance away from the notion that the guy who was making things happen was <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was asleep at the switch. `` It erases the notion of a passive president who's doing nothing,'' <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, said, `` It's nice to see the beginning of a response that everybody hoped there would be.'' Polls show <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has a positive rating of 66 to 73 percent, which puts him ahead of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at this point in his presidency. <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohut </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s approval rating was slipping in April and May but then began to turn around `` Between May and July, he's been dealing with international problems and the country tends to rally around a president who's dealing with rather clear-cut international issues,'' said <PERSON> Kohut </PERSON> On the other hand, <PERSON> Kohut </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is `` still an enigmatic character to many people. That's where he's weak.'' He said the category of people classified as `` do n't know'' or `` no opinion'' about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is higher than with other presidents, running at about 26 percent. Countering that criticism, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said `` vision does n't fit on a bumper sticker.'' He said the president is defining his agenda with specific proposals to balance the budget, bail out the savings and loan industry, clean up air pollution and combat crime. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has demonstrated `` a willingness to do his homework, to spend the time examining the details, then to make a decision not in haste.'' Asked what <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should have done differently, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> replied, `` Honest, in terms of the big issues and timetable and the agenda and the approach, not a heck of a lot.'' <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should be more aggressive, establish a long-term agenda and take some risks. Beyond that, he said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was losing `` an awful lot of direction and momentum'' by the fact that hundreds of top-level appointments have not been made. `` He could plummet the next six months if we slipped into a recession,'' cautioned <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>. `` There's a little too much basking in the glow of a 70 percent approval rating, not capitalizing on it,'' <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said. `` If you're up around 70 percent early on, it's a good time to let it drop down to 60 percent by pushing some things through that may be a little controversial.'' There is widespread agreement that much of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s popularity is due to his personal style, his high energy level and obvious relish for the job. `` I think we've grown used to him, like an old, comfortable shoe,'' said <PERSON> Hess </PERSON>. `` Some of the rough edges from the campaign have rubbed off. He has n't forced himself on us.'' <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` is not the kind of guy who's going to fall asleep with the pope'' _ alluding to an occasion where <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> nodded off while meeting with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said, `` I think people right off the bat perceived a different style'' from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> days. `` They have really begun to feel comfortable and appreciative of the style. I think that is very important for a president to do _ to give his mark to the office that he probably will be occupying for eight years.''
