<FIRST>r a PM-PsychiatristVideos Bjt   07-24 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Psychiatrist Videos, Bjt,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist Puts Expertise Into Videos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When it comes to teaching medical students about mental illness, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> does n't go by the book. He makes movies. `` A lot of the videotapes I make are designed to make people feel like they really are in the patient's shoes,'' said <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON>, an adolescent psychiatrist at <ORGANIZATION> Chestnut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> and an associate professor of psychiatry at <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Like, what does it feel like to be psychotic. The audience gets confused. They really begin to take on some of the feelings that are being portrayed.'' <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON>, 40, has produced more than 100 features since he began using videotapes as a teaching tool a decade ago while at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. About half are for sale to medical schools throughout the country. The videos range from 8 minutes to two hours in length and cost from $ 50 to $ 1,200. A year and a half ago, <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> began working on a new educational series called `` Medicine Playhouse'' at <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. Each episode presents an emotional, medical or philosophical problem typically faced by health professionals. A question-and-answer session with an expert in the field is held after each show. `` It's sort of a <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wobegone </LOCATION> approach to medical education,'' <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> said, referring to the mythical place made famous by humorist <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> on his radio show, `` A Prairie Home Companion.'' Students say the videos are a good learning tool. `` It's much more helpful for a medical student to observe a patient,'' said <PERSON> Kellie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gooding </PERSON>, 24, a third-year student at the medical school. `` It stays in your mind much longer if you can actually see a schizophrenic or whatever, rather than just reading about it. You might just remember something a couple of days if you read it. If you see it on the screen, you might remember it for the rest of your life.'' `` The videos show a really comprehensive picture,'' said <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON>, 23, also a third-year student. `` It shows you as it is _ real people in real life. In a book, they would break a subject down into one component and then another.'' Some of the videotapes, <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> said, make medical students squirm. In one video, shot in black-and-white and titled simply, `` Depression,'' a loud clock ticks in the background as cameras close in from different angles on the troubled face of an actor. `` It's just 15 minutes long but it seems like it runs for an eternity,'' <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> said. `` I've had people actually come up and tell me they feel suicidal after watching it, even though the word is never mentioned.'' In another, called `` Paranoia,'' a man grows more and more anxious as passengers riding on a city bus turn around in their seats and begin staring at him. He admits his videos may not be right for everyone. `` About 10 or 15 percent of the students do n't learn well using the videotapes,'' <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> said. `` They'd be better off with books or a lecture. Some people just are n't good visual learners. `` But that's OK. I do n't think many lectures in medical school reach 85 percent of the students,'' he said.
</TEXT>
