<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     07-24 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Considers Duty on Imports of Canadian Pork</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prospective <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> levy on imports of unprocessed fresh, chilled and frozen pork from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> could add further to a growing number of live hogs coming across the border, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analysis. Last week the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> ruled in a `` final determination'' that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s pork is being subsidized. The ruling now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which has 45 days to decide whether the imports are hurting American hog farmers. If the commission agrees with the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> ruling, the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> will be ordered to collect countervailing duties on imports of Canadian pork to offset the benefits of the subsidies. The Commerce investigation did not include processed or preserved pork products such as canned hams, bacon, sausage or ground pork. Countervailing duties have been levied on imports of live hogs from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> the past four years. Overall, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the world's largest pork importer, with about 1.14 billion pounds, carcass weight equivalent, imported last year, approximately 7 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumption, according to the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> supplied almost 45 percent of the 1988 pork imports; <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, 29 percent; and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, 11 percent. The remainder comes mainly from other Eastern European countries. Pork imports during the first four months of this year totaled about 333 million pounds, down 17 percent from January-April 1988, the report said. Imports from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> were `` substantially below'' the year-earlier level, while shipments from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were up slightly. `` Canadian hog and pork prices remain below last year, which has encouraged domestic consumption and diverted some supply from the export market,'' the report said. `` Despite near-record year-ago hog slaughter, Canadian statistics indicate that total exports of pork through the end of May were about 8 percent below 1988 levels.'' Earlier this year there was a wide spread between western Canadian hog prices and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prices, the report said. That provided a strong incentive for western Canadian producers to ship live hogs to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. The spread narrowed in April, and imports of live hogs from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> declined to less than half of their March level _ but still were 18 percent more than a year earlier. Hog imports from all sources for the January-April period totaled 475,845 head, the report said. That was 125 percent above the same period in 1988. Canadian production this year is expected to be down about 2 percent from 1988 because of herd liquidations prompted by lower hog prices. `` The addition of a countervailing duty deposit on fresh, chilled and frozen pork imports from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is expected to reinforce the existing shift towards imports of Canadian hogs,'' the report said. <PERSON> Shayle </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shagam </PERSON>, an economist in the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agency, said in another report that the world pork trade is small relative to total production and that a handful of countries are involved. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is the largest pork producer, accounting for almost a third of the world's total last year, but the country's huge population requires most of the production, <PERSON> Shagam </PERSON> said. Last year <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was the fourth largest pork exporter, with live hogs and pork going to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, and frozen pork to <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. On an individual country basis, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the second largest pork producer but ranks fourth when the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are included. As well as being the leading pork importer, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is sixth in the world as an exporter. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is the biggest market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pork. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is another large buyer. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> ranks seventh in the world as a pork producer, turning out much more than it requires domestically, <PERSON> Shagam </PERSON> said. Exports currently are about 22 percent of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s production. Almost 90 percent goes to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 9 percent to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> was third as an exporter last year. `` As a result of large domestic pork supplies, imports by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will remain fairly steady, with <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> increasing its relative share of the market,'' <PERSON> Shagam </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Shagam </PERSON> added that the mix between hogs and pork from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> will depend on relative wage rates in the meatpacking industry and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> countervailing duties on imports from there.
</TEXT>
