<HEAD>Bunker Says He's Trying to Forget Silver Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> says he's trying to forget the spring of 1980, when his silver-buying binge crashed to an end and began unraveling one of the world's greatest fortunes. He used to be in the oil business, in ranching and farming, he told <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Jules </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Korner </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. `` Lately, it's hiring lawyers and defending lawsuits. The Hunt brothers' tax case begins its third week today and is expected to last about a month. Bunker Hunt is contesting $ 155 million in 1982 taxes the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> says are owed from the dissolution of a partnership set up to pay off the brothers' debts. His brother <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> is contesting more than $ 158 million in 1982 taxes, while younger brother <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> football team, is contesting $ 505,377 in taxes. <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> testified Friday, `` I do n't go around trying to remember what happened in the spring of 1980. It caused me tremendous losses, it caused me tax problems.'' Banks once eager to lend him money `` were trying to get their arms around as much collateral as possible,'' he said _ to the point of demanding `` pictures on the wall'' and even his brother's Rolex watch <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> told the court he could not recall whether one document he signed was five or 5,000 pages long or whether he signed a promissory note for $ 272 million after Silver Thursday, the day in late March 1980 when silver prices collapsed. <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> owned one-third of the world's supply of silver bullion from a silver-shopping spree that began in 1973, government attorneys claim. As the price tumbled to $ 10 an ounce from $ 50 an ounce, the brothers found themselves with debts totaling as much as $ 2 billion and creditors threatening the family's beloved <ORGANIZATION> Placid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> creditors `` dictated'' the terms of the partnership with Placid set up to repay the Hunt brothers' debts from their soured silver investments, he said `` The net effect was we did n't have control over our business. That's why I'm sitting here in court, because of the structure the banks put us in,'' <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> said. Since then, <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> and Placid have filed for protection from creditors in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>; Bunker and <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> have been accused of attempting to corner the silver market by the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>; and a jury in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> last year found Bunker, <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> and two others had conspired to manipulate and monopolize the silver market and defraud investors. <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON>, the first of the brothers to testify in the non-jury trial, recalled one day after Silver Thursday when he signed documents while surrounded by attorneys. `` I signed documents for three or four hours, just as fast as I could,'' he said. `` There must have been thousands and thousands of documents I signed, they would probably go to the ceiling of this room here if they were stacked up end to end.'' <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> said he remembers <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Placid </PERSON>'s vice president and chief financial officer, telling him that the banks `` were calling all the shots, it was pretty much their party'' as they set up the partnership to repay the silver loans.
