ere,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> is the only <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> state with no Democrats in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Again, the Democrats would like to avoid a costly and divisive primary but it appears one is down the road. Conservative Democrat <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON>, a state senator and <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION> restaurateur, has already formed an exploratory campaign committee. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Keefe </PERSON>, an attorney and moderate who lost to <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> last year, says he's in it, too. And two others are looking, former state party chairman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> and stockbroker and party activist <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Demers </PERSON>, who ran in 1986. `` If all of us go at it ... I do n't think the seat is winnable,'' warns <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON>, urging the national officials to do what they can to help avoid a primary.
