<HEAD>Workers Flex New-Found Muscle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Strikes, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROKOPYEVSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Every working day, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kutlakhmetov </PERSON> boards an orange bus with six shoulder-high wheels that carries him and other miners 43 miles across the rolling Siberian plateau to the Taldinski Severni Open Pit Mine. On Friday, <PERSON> Kutlakhmetov </PERSON>, known as <PERSON> Sasha </PERSON>, boarded the bus for the first time in more than a week. He sped off to explain to other miners the details of a 35-point agreement that ended the first Soviet industrial strike in 60 years. Lurching along the bumpy, thinly asphalted road that links city and mine, the bus passed birch, aspen and pine forests, tiny settlements of log cabins with carved wooden trims and kitchen gardens. Small herds of goats and cows, and an occasional horse, could be seen in the lanes. As the sun rose slowly, burning off a thick morning mist, the bus arrived at the pit's brick headquarters, and the miners began to slap each other's shoulders in greeting and discuss the agreement that ended their unprecedented strike. <PERSON> Sasha </PERSON> stepped up to the landing and, waving the agreement, began to explain. `` Do we get three years maternity leave?'' shouted one woman, who worked in the mine offices. `` That's in there,'' replied <PERSON> Sasha </PERSON>. `` What about the time it takes us to get here on the bus?'' shouted a man. `` We'll get paid from the time we check in, but not for commuting,'' said <PERSON> Sasha </PERSON>. The session continued for a half hour, as miners asked about grievances that were advanced at Taldinski Severni but may or may not have been included in the demands of the strike committee formed the week before for the <LOCATION> Kuznetsk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>, the country's second largest coal-producing region At last, the workers were satisfied that if they had not won every point, they had at least seized the right to strike, a right not guaranteed by Soviet law. They beamed with new-found confidence. `` It's a victory over the system that we've had in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for the past 70 years, a system in which we work hard but get little in return,'' said <PERSON> Pyotr </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Menayev </PERSON>, an engineer. Another miner, <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sizikov </PERSON>, agreed that it was a victory, but `` it would have been a bigger victory if we had continued the strike.'' Sensitive to the doubts of miners like <PERSON> Sizikov </PERSON>, the regional strike committee renamed itself the <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and remained in session to pressure authorities to keep the bargain. `` If they do n't, we go back on strike. That's in the agreement,'' said <PERSON> Kutlakhmetov </PERSON>. Mine managers, who backed most of the strike demands, were pleased at the most import government concession _ allowing mines to form local assocations that will have a greater say in running the industry, which remains under the general control of the <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is better to be master in your own house,'' said <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevnin </PERSON>, the main production engineer at the mine. `` The strike will improve our lives. And the agreement will move us closer to real economic independence.'' The miners, still skeptical of the government's intention of keeping the deal, boarded the bus once again to drive the final few miles to the pit. Deep down in the crater, <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Demski </PERSON> clambered into the cabin of a giant crane and began using the controls to scoop small mountains of coal into oversize dump trucks, resuming delivery of fuel to the state. `` We got little concrete,'' said <PERSON> Demski </PERSON>, as he operated the shovel. `` Maybe there will be more.'' Another worker in the crane cabin, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorlov </PERSON>, nodded his head, and said, `` It was right to strike.''
</TEXT>
