<HEAD>Mecham Still Looms Large on Arizona Political Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a year after former Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was driven from office in disgrace, he casts a shadow over <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> politics as he campaigns to regain his old job. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s conservative ideas dominate the Republican agenda and his successor, Democratic Gov. Rose Mofford, has been unable to marshal support in her own party or win battles with the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> majority in the Legislature. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was elected in 1986 in a three-way race; he got just 40 percent of the vote. That inspired a law requiring the governor to receive at least 50 percent of the vote. Some <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> supporters admit he would have trouble winning a clear majority. But they say he may have enough solid support to overcome any moderate Republican opponent in the primary. That leaves many Republicans in a quandary. What they'd really like, said freshman state Sen. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON>, is `` somebody with <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s philosophy but not his cantankerousness, at least as he's been portrayed. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, whose only opponent so far is millionaire developer <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fife </PERSON> <PERSON> Symington </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, exudes confidence about the September 1990 primary, and the general election that follows. `` I'm going to win the cotton-picking election,'' he said. `` You can mark that on the wall if you wish.'' The blunt-talking, 65-year-old auto dealer with four failed gubernatorial campaigns behind him stunned <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> with his 1986 victory. From the start, he demonstrated a remarkable ability to offend many groups. In his first month in office, he rescinded the state's <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> holiday, questioning the civil rights leader's stature and saying that former Gov <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON> had lacked the authority to decree the holiday. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> also endorsed a book that characterized blacks as `` pickaninnies,'' stated that a political enemy was spying on him with laser beams, and was reported to have associates with criminal records. He was impeached in February 1988 on charges of misusing a state protocol fund, obstructing a probe into a death threat and concealing a developer's $ 350,000 campaign loan. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted and ousted him two months later on the first two charges before voters could make their own decision in a recall election that had been scheduled for May. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> dropped the loan concealment charge, and a jury subsequently acquitted him of wrongdoing. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> earlier this month challenged his impeachment and demanded the reinstatement of $ 570,000 in expenses. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was succeeded by Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, who since 1975 had been secretary of state, a largely ceremonial, elected post similar to the lieutenant governor in other states. Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> enjoyed popularity and bipartisan support early on, but she failed to get her way on several key issues during the legislative session that ended in June. Moderate Republicans sided with conservatives in opposing Mofford initiatives to increase taxes and spending, instead cutting the state's contribution to government pension funds. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> has advocated slashing taxes and state spending. The Legislature also defeated Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>'s bid to restore the King holiday. `` Rose basically is still trying to find her sea legs,'' said state Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Goudinoff </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> political science professor. Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, 67, said she will run for re-election, although aides say she has n't yet begun fundraising. No other <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate has announced. The perfect candidate, <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON> said, would combine <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s conservatism with Mofford's geniality Some sense the impeachment is unfinished business for many Arizonans. `` I think <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> needs to vote on the <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> situation,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who cast one of the few votes against impeachment last year. Still, she added, `` We can not allow any one person to be the issue of the campaign.''
