<HEAD>Debt Reduction Vital To Economic Recovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Mexico-Debt, Bjt ^By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The agreement with foreign banks to reduce <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s debt burden will give <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> both more cash for investment and an important psychological boost after years of austerity and stagnation. `` The resources that were being sent outside the country can now be channeled into investment, growth and creating jobs,'' President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> said in a triumphant televised address Sunday night. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s total debt burden is estimated at $ 107 billion _ with $ 54 billion owed to private banks _ and the agreement is expected to cut billions from the amount <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has to pay to service its debt to the banks. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> got into trouble during the oil boom, when developing nations and banks thought the price of oil would keep going up. When the price crashed in 1982, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was suddenly left without enough money to make payments on the billions it had borrowed. The result was six years of belt-tightening under the administration of President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. The government had to take harsh measures to get the money to make payments and that left little for development. Private companies, too, could n't borrow money to invest in new plants or equipment. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s economy slowed down and inflation went up _ to over 150 percent annually some years. The peso dropped like a brick against the dollar from eight to the dollar in the mid-1970s to 2,500 to the dollar today. The average Mexican paycheck lost about half its buying power. The austerity affected everything from the peso to pollution _ 95 percent of all cars in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> are more than five years old, most bought before the crash. `` Every day we worked harder but we were worse off,'' <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> said. The country of 85 million was under additional social pressure because of demographics. One million young people were entering the job market every year, but the country had trouble creating even half that many jobs. The pressure was also visible in the erosion of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s power in last year's presidential election <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> won with barely 50 percent of the vote, the lowest margin in the history of a party that has given <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> 60 years of stable government. Some of the pressure was relieved by emigration, which continues as one of many factors that gives the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> an interest in its southern neighbor's stability. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was able to argue that it deserved consideration from the banks because it had done everything asked by creditors and had worked hard to restructure its economy. It joined the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and stopped protecting its economy from foreign competition. The idea, which has been working, was to reduce prices in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and make Mexican industry more competitive on international markets. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> was careful to get President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and institutions such as the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> on board before tackling the private banks that were reluctant to write off billions in debt. He also made dramatic crackdowns on corruption and the drug trafficking that had infuriated the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In his speech, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> said that some of the money saved under the new agreement will go to building infrastructure _ roads, dams, communications _ that he hopes will lay the basis for an eventual growth rate of 6 percent a year. Economists say part of what <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> gains will go to buying back debt at a discount. The rest can be used for investment in infrastructure that could prime the pump for the private sector. With fewer payments to make the government will need to borrow less money, putting less pressure on domestic credit markets and making more available for the private sector at lower rates. More importantly, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> hopes increased confidence and the perception of victory will attract foreign investment and help bring back billions invested abroad by wealthy Mexicans. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> warned his countrymen, economic recovery will not come overnight. `` The agreement does not mean that by some magic trick our problems will cease to exist,'' he said. He promised firm guidance of the economy and honest management of the nation's resources. `` Everybody must continue pushing productivity and maintaining order,'' <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> said.
