<HEAD>A Caretaker Prime Minister Who Didn't Last</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Japan, Bjt ^By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> became prime minister on June 2, he was widely expected to be a caretaker who with luck might serve until October while his scandal-plagued party put together a political reform package. His luck turned out to be very bad. Now he will go down in Japanese postwar history as rivaling for shortness the two-month tenure that Prime Minister <PERSON> Tanzan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishibashi </PERSON> had from December 1956 to February 1957. Seldom has a respectable political career crumbled as fast as Uno's. He was in office less than a week when a weekly newsmagazine published a former geisha's allegation that he had paid her to be his mistress. Publishing the story broke a taboo about revealing details of politicians' private affairs. The 66-year-old Uno, who is married, was deeply embarrassed facing opposition questions in parliament as to whether he was suitable to represent <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> abroad when his ex-mistress had complained in print about the way he had treated her. It was about the last thing <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> might have expected to happen to him. Elders in his <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> selected him to be prime minister because his experience as foreign minister would stand <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in good diplomatic stead. He was clean of the bribery scandal that ruled out all the prime ministerial contenders in the party, and otherwise uncontroversial. But allegations against Uno widened, with publications finding other women who claimed sexual relations with him. On June 28, Japanese papers reported that <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> had asked party leaders to let him resign because of the embarrassment. `` I did n't become prime minister because I wanted to,'' Uno was quoted as saying. But he was persuaded to stay on. He attended the summit of the world's seven leading industrial democracies in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in mid-July and led the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> into what became their worst electoral defeat in three decades in Sunday's voting for half the seats in the upper house of Parliament. <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>'s `` woman problem,'' as Japanese media dubbed his personal scandal, was one of many the Liberal Democrats faced in the election campaign. They were distrusted because of the bribery scandal, disliked because of a new sales tax imposed in April, suspected because market-liberalization measures were seen threatening the livelihoods of farmers. This morning, <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> was calm as he faced reporters and said he would leave office as soon as the party could replace him. `` Ultimate responsibility'' for the election defeat was his, he said, and he hoped the party would choose a new head `` promptly.'' If that process, as expected, takes three or four weeks, Uno will not go down in history as beating Ishibashi's record for a short tenure. But it will be a close call.
