<HEAD>More Convicted Drug Traffickers Hanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> today hanged 22 people convicted of drug smuggling or prostitution, including nine women and four Afghan nationals, the official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. The agency, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, said the men were hanged in public squares around <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and the women at a jail outside the capital. It said they were convicted of smuggling, selling and distributing heroin and opium, prostitution and spreading corruption. The hangings brought to 810 the number of officially reported executions under an anti-narcotics law that mandates the death penalty for possession of even small quantities of drugs. The law took effect in January. <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> said a six-month grace period for addicts to kick the habit expired Sunday and they would be rounded up and sent to labor camps and other rehabilitation centers. Law enforcement officials have said they have identified 80 percent of Iranian drug addicts. Authorities have said that 1 million Iranians are involved in drug abuse but unofficial estimates put the figure at 2 million of the country's 50 million population.
