<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> announced today he will resign after his scandal-plagued party suffered a stinging electoral defeat, losing control of a house of parliament for the first time in its 34 years. `` It was a very difficult election,'' <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> told a nationally televised news conference. Uno has been prime minister less than two months, but he said his party's loss of control of parliament's upper house in Sunday elections ultimately is his responsibility. The long-governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> have seen their popularity plummet over an influence-peddling scandal, a new 3 percent sales tax and the liberalization of agricultural imports, which farmers say hurts their livelihood. Uno has been criticized for alleged extramarital affairs, including with a geisha who said he paid her to be his mistress for several months. He said he hoped a successor could be found `` promptly.'' Analysts said the process could take several weeks. <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>'s resignation will result in the dissolution of the Cabinet and restructuring of the governing party's leadership. But some <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> said this would not solve the problems. `` It's a question of why we lost,'' said <PERSON> Yohei </PERSON> <PERSON> Koono </PERSON>, a liberal lower house lawmaker. `` If our choice of policies is wrong, we need to change it.'' Business leaders urged thorough political reforms from the party that guided <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s rapid postwar economic growth. `` We should not allow this to have an adverse effect on economic activity or the people's lives,'' said <PERSON> Eishiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Saito </PERSON>, chairman of the powerful <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION>. In the balloting for half the 252 seats in parliament's upper house, the big winner was the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, led by <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON>, the first woman leader of a major <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> party. Of 126 seats at stake, the Socialists won 46, the Liberal Democrats 36. The Socialists' total strength in the chamber rose from 43 to 66; the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>' fell from 142 to 109. <ORGANIZATION> Rengo </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Confederation -RRB-, a new labor-based group, won 11 seats and the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> 10, with the rest split among smaller parties. Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> said her party quickly will call a meeting of opposition leaders to form a coalition against the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, who still hold 293 of the 512 seats in parliament's more powerful lower house. Any coalition is expected to be fragile. While most major opposition parties have called for abolishing the new sales tax, they vary broadly on other issues such as defense policy, relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and nuclear power. With the loss of their majority in the upper house, however, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> will face greater difficulties in passing legislation. The upper chamber can vote down bills and delay, but not block, the budget and treaties. Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> called her party's victory `` the people's verdict,'' and said <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>'s decision to step down was `` only natural.'' She said the Socialists' first priority is to pass a bill in the upper house abolishing the sales tax. Such a bill is unlikely to be approved by the lower house, however, and a standstill over the issue could add to pressure for early elections for the lower chamber. Legally, they do not have to be held for 12 months. A loss in the lower house would threaten the governing party's 34-year hold on power since that chamber chooses the prime minister About 65 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 90.3 million eligible voters cast ballots in Sunday's election, reflecting strong feelings over issues affecting many people's everyday lives. Women were particularly unhappy over the new sales tax, bulldozed through by the governing party despite an opposition boycott. `` I really believe that this was a people's revolution coming from the kitchen,'' said <PERSON> Kazuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinsaka </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Rengo </ORGANIZATION> candidate who won election in <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION>. A record 146 women candidates ran for office Sunday, and a record 22 were elected, more than doubling female representation in the chamber. `` One result of the election is that Japanese politicians from now on will have to pay more attention to women,'' said <PERSON> Seisaburo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sato </PERSON>, professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Though Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> is immensely popular, her party has been widely accused of lacking a realistic and constructive platform. In the past, it has called for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to disband its Self-Defense Forces and scrap the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION>, under which 64,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops are stationed in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Socialist leaders now say they would not immediately do away with the armed forces and seek only to revise the treaty. <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> became prime minister June 2 after former Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> resigned to take responsibility for a scandal in which the <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a publishing conglomerate, allegedly distributed millions of dollars in underpriced stocks and political donations to obtain favors. The governing party spent weeks finding an unsullied successor for <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>. But shortly after taking office, <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> was linked to the sex scandal. Asked how he felt after announcing his resignation, Uno, a poet, said, `` My state of mind is ` meikyo shisui''' _ meaning tranquil as unrippled water.
