<HEAD>Israel Court Says Government Must Recognize Jewish Conversions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 4 grafs of comment from U.S. groups.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that the government must recognize Jewish conversions conducted abroad by <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> rabbis, deciding an issue that has put many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews at odds with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The 4-1 decision immediately caused friction in Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s Cabinet, where religious parties protested and one faction threatened to resign. In a second decision, the court unanimously rejected an appeal to allow Reform rabbis to perform marriages in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. That decision upheld an Orthodox monopoly on conducting religious weddings. Both of today's rulings were linked to the issue of `` Who is a Jew?'' Israeli Orthodox Jews have sought to narrow that definition under the Law of Return. The law now permits granting Israeli citizenship to anyone born of a Jewish mother or who has converted to Judaism and does not belong to another faith. The Orthodox want the definition to include only Jews born to Jewish mothers or converted according to Jewish law known as Halacha, which would effectively mean by Orthodox rabbis. The change has been fought by Conservative and Reform rabbis, whose followers constitute a majority of more than 5 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews but who have few adherents in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The Reform and Conservative Jews contend the Orthodox proposal would symbolically excommunicate them from Judaism and alienate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Rabbis estimate there are more than 10,000 conversions a year in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, nearly all non-Orthodox. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, headed by Chief Justice <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamgar </PERSON>, made today's decision in a ruling on appeals by 12 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> immigrants and one from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. They were denied Israeli citizenship papers by the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, which is controlled by the ultra-Orthodox <ORGANIZATION> Shas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The court's 17-page ruling said a 1965 Israeli law did not entitle the government to decide the validity of conversions by different Jewish groups. Religious Affairs Minister <PERSON> Zevulun </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> reacted to the ruling by pledging to renew a political campaign for a narrower definition of who is a Jew, <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Porush </PERSON>, a legislator of the ultra-Orthodox Agudat <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> faction, said his party may withdraw its support from <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s Cabinet. Such a move could sway other religious parties to take similar actions. `` We have a secular court interfering in a religious subject. We must view this very seriously,'' <PERSON> Porush </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Agudat is participating in the government for the first time. It has traditionally refused to do so to avoid dealing in secular affairs. The party holds five seats in the 120-seat Parliament. Its executive council scheduled a meeting for later today to discuss the issue. <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Moskowitz </PERSON>, one of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> immigrants in the court case, said: `` I have been waiting for this for 2 -LCB- years. That's a long time to not know where you stand. Now I know where I stand: on my own feet and I'm Jewish.'' `` I believe it is important to separate the issue of church and state,'' said <PERSON> Elissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Rafael </PERSON>, a plaintiff from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. She joined the suit even though she was converted by an Orthodox rabbi. The marriage ruling came on appeals made seven years ago by the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> rabbi <PERSON> Mordechai </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotem </PERSON>; and a rabbi from <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemer </PERSON>. In the 97-page decision, the justices upheld three laws which effectively give <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Orthodox rabbis exclusive rights to decide who may preside at marriages. Spokesman for several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> groups said they were pleased by the decision on conversions. `` We believe that the court's action helps to preserve the unity of the Jewish people so essential to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> at the present critical time,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gruen </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> affairs for the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> Jewish Committee in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I say hallelujah,'' said <PERSON> Carmela </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalmanson </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Hadassah </ORGANIZATION>, a women's Zionist organization in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> with 385,000 members. Ms. <PERSON> Kalmanson </PERSON> said that though the numbers of people affected `` may be small, it was the perception that was very hurtful.''
