<HEAD>Aquino Admits Filipinos Still Poor; Teachers Demand Pay Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> told legislators Monday that most Filipinos remain poor despite economic gains during her three-year rule. In an address to a joint session of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> repeated promises to rid her government of tax cheaters and grafters, and to purge the police and military of criminals who made the crime situation `` nothing less than terrible.'' As she spoke, about 3,000 members of left-wing organizations marched to protest corruption and alleged foreign control of Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s government and economic policies. Another group of about 3,000 public school teachers demonstrated separately to demand salary increases. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said that despite a 20-year communist insurgency and at least six coup attempts, her government succeeded in the past three years in reviving the economy, increasing investment, reducing unemployment and nibbling away at mass poverty. But the recovery `` has restored old fortunes far more significantly than it has touched the lives of the vast majority'' of more than 55 million Filipinos, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said. `` Poverty has lessened but 5.3 million households, or 29 million people, remain poor,'' she said. `` Unemployment has been reduced, but try telling that to the 2.9 million still jobless and the 7.2 million underemployed.'' Even the 500,000 families which statistically have crossed the poverty line _ a monthly income of $ 119 for a family of six _ feel nothing has changed, she said. `` I ca n't blame them: liberty is a poor substitute for food.'' She announced measures to help develop the countryside, where most Filipinos live. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said she is `` tired of being taken to task'' for continuing corruption and wants to leave clean and honest government as her legacy. `` To my fellow workers in government specifically involved in this area and in all other areas as well, let me say that unless the public sees results soon, it will be good-bye for you,'' she said. `` The compassion that marked my administration in the past may generate doubts about my resolve in this matter, but the actions that will be taken by me in the next weeks and months will dispel them all.''
