<HEAD>Administration Expects Close Ties with Japan to Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration expects close ties with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to continue regardless of who is chosen to succeed the fallen government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said today. <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s spokesman, said he had no direct comment on the election results in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> `` simply because it's an internal matter.'' `` However, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has long and strong relationships with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. We certainly would expect those to continue under any successor government,'' said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. `` We do n't have any idea who that successor will be. But whoever it is we look forward to working with them, to establishing friendly and productive ties of a kind that we have had in the past,'' he said. <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> and his ruling <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> lost its majority in the upper house of the Diet for the first time in 34 years. <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> announced today he would resign, saying he accepted `` the responsibility for this defeat wholly upon myself.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are bound by their trading ties and militarily. `` We would expect to maintain all of those ties in a solid fashion,'' he said. But he said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government would continue to `` press rather vigorously'' with the new government on trade problems. `` That can be done in a positive fashion, and that's the way we expect to do it,'' he said.
