<HEAD>White House Expects Close Ties With Japan to Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it expects to maintain close ties with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> regardless of who succeeds the fallen <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> as prime minister. <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s spokesman, said Sunday's elections, in which <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> lost control of the upper house of parliament, were `` an internal matter. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has long and strong relationships with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` We certainly would expect those to continue under any successor government.'' Uno announced Monday he would resign as prime minister. His resignation will open the way to dissolving <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>'s Cabinet and restructuring the governing party's leadership. `` We do n't have any idea who that successor will be,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s spokesman said `` But, whoever it is, we look forward to working with them, to establishing friendly and productive ties of a kind that we have had in the past.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are bound economically and militarily, and `` we would expect to maintain all of those ties in a solid fashion.'' But he said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government would continue to `` press rather vigorously'' on trade problems with the new government. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> also said that a non-binding congressional resolution calling for restrictions on the FSX jet fighter deal with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> `` faces a very heavy veto threat'' from the president. Several senior advisers have urged <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to reject the measure as an intrusion on executive branch deliberations and because it `` compromises the president's ability'' to manage foreign affairs, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has until July 31 to act on the FSX resolution, but will probably make his decision before then, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. Regardless of what course <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> takes, the joint development deal will go through because the congressional resolution is non-binding, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> never passed a binding resolution disapproving the joint venture. Under the FSX deal, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heavy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> will jointly develop the new fighter for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> based on an improved F-16 design. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> had been set to develop a jet fighter by itself until then-Defense Secrtary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> talked the Japanese into the joint development, which ensures <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies 40 percent of the revenues from the project. Critics in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and elsewhere have charged the deal will give the Japanese access to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> technology they could use to develop a domestic airplane industry.
