<HEAD>Secretary of State To Attend Weekend Talks in Paris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> will attend a conference on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s future next weekend in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, working for a settlement that rules out a return to power of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced today. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> probably will meet there with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. That session could begin preliminary planning for a summit meeting between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The month-long conference, involving the five permanent members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ is designed to map out <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s future after the last Vietnamese troops leave the country at the end of September `` We hope our collective efforts can become another example of how we, the Soviets and others can work together to resolve regional conflicts,'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said in making the announcement. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and the other foreign ministers plan to attend the opening session. The conference will then proceed through the month of August in the form of working-level groups. The departure of Vietnamese troops, which backed up a pro-Hanoi and pro-Moscow government in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>, was long a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign policy goal. `` With an international, verified Vietnamese withdrawal, we hope to see a beginning of an end to the tragedy that has beset the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people for years, and a beginning of a transition to genuine Cambodian self-determination,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. Her statement said a settlement had to ensure peace in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by containing three key elements: _ A verified withdrawal of Vietnamese forces _ Prevention of a return to power by the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, who have been implicated in the killings of as many as 1 million Cambodians during the 1970s _ Self-determination for the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people `` Given the legacy of warfare in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and the tragedies of the past it will be difficult to achieve peace,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said. `` But it is necessary to try. It is time to at least try to end the suffering of the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people. We hope the day is near when the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people will be able to live in peace and achieve true self-determination.''
