<HEAD>Honeywell Announces Sweeping Plan To Enhance Shareholder Value</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT to annual dividend, sted fourth-quarter;
A version moved on the business wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, subject of intense takeover speculation for the past several weeks, said today it will cut 4,000 jobs, reduce its weapons business, repurchase shares and increase dividends. The sweeping restructuring will result in a 65-cent increase in the company's annual dividend, to $ 2.75 a share, and possibly include a special cash dividend, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Renier </PERSON>, chairman of the controls maker and defense contractor. The news prompted a sharp increase in <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> stock on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. In early morning trading, the stock was up $ 3.75 a share to $ 89.25. The program will include the sale of a `` substantial portion'' of <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s 50 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Yamatake-Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese controls maker, <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said. Analysts have valued the holding at about $ 1 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> also will reduce its weapons business, which accounts for about 20 percent of its revenues. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON> would not say if a sale of the business is one of the options being considered. The program will include elimination of 4,000 jobs worldwide over the next 18 months, including 300 corporate staff positions targeted in a previous announcement. <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON> said the company is not ready to announce specific locations for the job cuts. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> employs about 78,000 workers worldwide. Many of the job losses will come through attrition, but layoffs will be necessary, <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors also has broadened a company stock repurchase plan from about 3.5 million shares to 10 million shares. The stock will be bought on the open market, <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said. The program should improve operating profits by about $ 150 million over the next 18 months, <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said. Negotiations to sell the company's stake in <ORGANIZATION> Yamatake-Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>, which is listed on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, will begin within a few days, <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON> said. She would not identify potential buyers. Japanese investors currently own half of the company, she said. <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said the reduction of <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s weapons business is part of a strategy begun in 1988 to `` concentrate on core controls businesses that principally serve commercial markets as well as the market for military and space controls.'' <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> is the leading manufacturer of torpedoes for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and also supplies small, medium and large ammunition to the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON> said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McManus </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said the action could deter a takeover attempt, but not guarantee independence for <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>. `` They are trying to basically boost the stock price to make it more difficult for someone to take them over,'' <PERSON> McManus </PERSON> said. `` It will also alleviate some of the large shareholders who have been pounding on the door.'' <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price has risen sharply in the last two weeks following published reports that <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was considering acquiring the company.
