<HEAD>Sex Offenders Waive Chance at Parole to Seek Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNION SPRINGS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> inmates have temporarily waived their chances at parole so they can participate in an 18-month prison treatment program for sex offenders. Convicted rapist <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON> said in an interview last week that agreeing to give up a May 1990 parole review, his first, was not difficult. `` I need the treatment more than I need my freedom,'' said <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON>, 28, serving a 10-year sentence imposed in 1986. Because of his commitment to the program he and the four others are next due for parole consideration in January 1991. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, in prison for 16 years since being convicted of rape, said waiving his chance to escape a 99-year term was the only way he had to help himself. He was to have had a February 1990 parole hearing. `` I came to the conclusion that if they let me out on the day I was thinking about, I would be back here in a month,'' said <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, 38, previously denied release in 1986 and 1988. `` I do n't want no more victims. <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> and the other three who waived parole hearing dates are among 26 inmates participating in the state's sexual offender treatment program at the <ORGANIZATION> Bullock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facility </ORGANIZATION>, said director <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyk </PERSON>. The five are the first to give up a chance at release to seek treatment. The five were required to sign away their chance at parole during the 18-month period to ensure they would be able to finish therapy, said <PERSON> Merle </PERSON> <PERSON> Frieson </PERSON>, director of mental health treatment for the state prison system. The program includes group sessions and exercises to enable inmates to overcome sexual arousal that leads to acts like rape and child molestation, <PERSON> Frieson </PERSON> said. `` The treatment is rugged enough ... that you have to have to be highly motivated to complete it,'' he said. Ms. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyk </PERSON> said only inmates who admit to their crimes and to having a sex-related problem are admitted to the program. For inmate <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> McLoyd </PERSON>, confessing that he was the only one responsible for his 1978 rape conviction was the hardest part. `` I did what I wanted to do. My thinking was just so twisted, distorted,'' a weeping <PERSON> McLoyd </PERSON> said last week. He has been denied parole three times and put off his next hearing for nine months to enter the program. Ms. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyk </PERSON> said the treatment is intended to teach inmates how to control their perverse desires when confronted with situations they find sexually exciting. While the men might always be excited by certain images or sounds, Ms. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyk </PERSON> said, they can learn to quell their dangerous impulses. `` We're not curing anything. We're teaching people to control their arousal,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyk </PERSON> said officials do not know if the program is a success. Of 26 inmates who have completed the 18-month program, none has gone before the parole board and only one has completed his sentence. `` And the real test is when they get back on the street,'' she said. A similar program in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has had a 50 percent to 60 percent success rate in steering sex offenders away from more assaults, Ms. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyk </PERSON> said, and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> officials would be pleased with similar results. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pardons </ORGANIZATION> and Paroles, said he was unsure how the board would look upon sex offenders who have completed the program. But while the board is reluctant to release rapists and child molesters, he said, the inmates' willingness to stay in prison for treatment is `` rather remarkable.''
