<HEAD>3 Drown in Treacherous Ocean Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SURFSIDE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 High wind created treacherous currents in which three tourists drowned off unguarded southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> beaches, and <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> lifeguards made at least 15 successful rescues, officials said. Beach Patrol Chief <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Sforza </PERSON> said the rip-tide remained dangerous Monday. `` It's insidious,'' he said. While the patrol did n't close the beaches Sunday, swimmers were warned to avoid the currents after the first two drownings. But many stayed in the ocean _ some within sight of the blanket-covered corpses on the beach. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said strong easterly wind caused rip currents, which develop when strong waves bring a lot of water close to the shore. The water then opens up gaps in sandbars and rushes back out to the ocean through channels. `` With each days you have same conditions, it exacerbates the rip currents,'' <PERSON> Sforza </PERSON> said. `` You get more and more sandbar breaks up and down the coast, so you have more rip currents.''
