<HEAD>Poland Takes Pride in its Knights</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WAR52,53</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 GOLUB-DOBRZYN, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ These may be beleaguered days for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, but it does have its knights. The 15th century came alive this weekend, at an international tournament recalling the valor and vigor of a period of vast power. For a day, about 25,000 people put aside their economic woes that beset modern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to be transformed back to an era of pageantry, with knights atop their steeds testing their jousting skills according to regulations culled from historic records. `` It was the greatest age in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s history,'' says <PERSON> Zygumnt </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwiatkowski </PERSON>, director of the castle that was the site of an annual competition that saw knights from four countries in a pitched battle. `` <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> was independent then and was a peaceful superpower in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> never sought war with anyon and on the other hand it could counter any war threat.'' The tournament has been staged since 1977 on the grounds of the hulking brick castle that rises from a bluff, overlooking the apartment blocks of the central <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Golub-Dobrzyn </LOCATION>. At their aid are damsels recruited from a local high school; competitors with crossbows, hatchets and pronged mallets; and thousands of common spectators whose murmers of respect and rumor _ `` Someone almost had his nose sliced off'' _ spread the spirit of the event. `` When I see the knights, I think about reviving old traditions of knighthood,'' said <PERSON> Kwiatkowski </PERSON>. `` It is not only the clothes but also reviving the spirit, the old traditions: honesty, keeping promises, honor. These are features that today have lost their value but without which it is hard to live,'' he said. Though bogged down by the demands of a modern knight-manager, the castle director says he could still `` get on a horse and defend the honor of the Polish knight.'' Those responsibilities fall mainly to the likes of <ORGANIZATION> Remigiusz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postolski </ORGANIZATION>, a 30-year-old <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> art restorer who with his teammates bested the knights from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> <PERSON> Paulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Parici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arezzo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, was awarded the golden sword for individual performance at the close of hostilities Sunday. `` Almost every boy in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> when he is small reads books and watches films about knights and their fights. For me it passed into a more serious interest,'' <PERSON> Postolski </PERSON> said. Most of the weapons, armor and costumes are made by hand, and modern knights must make some accommodations. Suits of armor ended with <ORGANIZATION> Reebok </ORGANIZATION> sneakers and one crossbow champion wore skintight leggings of hot pink and black Spandex below his coat of mail. There's also the problem of how to sit on a slatted bench with a dagger at one's side. The castle, too, has met the modern age. The knights' pledge of princely competition is made by microphone, and a TV antenna rises from the ramparts. Flags and tablets mark great dates in castle history: 1296, 1527, 1965. The castle is owned by a government tourist agency. Much reconstructed from the ravages wrought by time and neglect, it is still in need of defense fortifications against tourists without tickets. But the hobbyists are loyal to the legends starting in 1385 when <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, united with <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> under the <ORGANIZATION> Jagiellonian </ORGANIZATION> kings, ruled a vast swath of central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> from the Baltic to the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and stretching east toward <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. It was a time of cultural and scientific advancement, when <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Copernicus </PERSON> discovered the Earth's rotation around the sun and the <ORGANIZATION> Jagiellonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> was established in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>. But from a Polish knight's point of view, the era's highlight was likely the victory over the infamous Teutonic Knights, a Germanic order first established in 1191 for the Crusades. The most famous confrontation, the Battle of <PERSON> Grunwald </PERSON> on July 15, 1410, took place about 50 miles from the castle and the victory of the Polish and Lithuanian forces over the Teutonic camp _ after a knightly pre-battle exchange of swords _ has lived on into the modern history of three nations. <PERSON> Kwiatkowski </PERSON> is an animated and unabashed fan of the 15th century. What about poverty? `` It's exaggerated. We have much bigger extremes in wealth today.'' What about pestilence? `` What about AIDS?'' he retorts. `` We Poles have a kind of attraction to tradition and history,'' added <PERSON> Postolski </PERSON>, whose sword bore the nicks of a few `` friendly'' rounds. `` At that time our country was a European superpower.''
