<HEAD>Vienna _ Traditional Center for East-West Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The investigation of senior diplomat <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> on suspicion he spied for the Soviets has again turned the spotlight on <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> as a hotbed of East-West espionage and intrigue. <PERSON> Orson </PERSON> <PERSON> Welles </PERSON>' depiction of <ORGANIZATION> Harry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lime </ORGANIZATION> in the 1949 film `` The Third Man'' stamped on the minds of millions an image of devious dealings in the Austrian capital, which, like <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, was divided into British, French, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Soviet sectors after World War II. Former Nazis and refugees from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> struggled to survive in the postwar turmoil, selling knowledge to any side that would pay and helping to weave a net of intrigue. The Soviets withdrew their forces from <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> in 1955, but they left behind a large embassy and many other offices that Western intelligence agencies always have viewed as potential helpers of the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> GRU </ORGANIZATION>, Soviet military intelligence. Intelligence sources in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> say nearly every American taken to court on charges of spying for the Soviets in the past five years had come to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> to meet <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> officers. The Soviets are as aware as the Americans that these trips often are part of the evidence used by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. Some intelligence sources believe, therefore, that one purpose of the trip to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> is to get a blackmail hold over the American, threatening exposure of a hard-to-explain journey if he wants to wriggle out of his deal with the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>. Americans who have made <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> trips include <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelton </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> officer who tipped <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to a system that hid <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> submarines from Soviet radar, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, head of the family spy ring in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. Court documents in the <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> case included written instructions from the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> about how to `` drop'' information, including a detailed description of doing a walking `` pass'' on a <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> street. It was also in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Marine </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Lonetree </PERSON> confessed to a security breach in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. A Soviet defector who worked for the <ORGANIZATION> GRU </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in the 1970s described <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s elaborate intelligence network in the Austrian capital in a 1985 memoir, `` Aquarium,'' published in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Suvorov </PERSON> -LRB- not his real name -RRB- said detailed procedures were worked out to avoid immediate identification by Austrian and other security services in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> of agents in the embassy. He estimated about 80 percent of all Soviets in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> _ where <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has an <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> office, trade representations, and a large diplomatic presence at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> _ engaged in `` other work'' outside their official duties. Part of the elaborate coverup of Soviet intelligence work, according to <PERSON> Suvorov </PERSON>, was to assign active agents, such as himself, mostly to work outside <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. But most of the work, he said, focused on acquiring Western technology and contingency plans for military or economic crises. It is not known what information, if any, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> handed to the Soviets during his seven years in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, where he arrived in 1980 as head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>'s economics section. He became deputy chief of mission, a post he held for years before returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1987. However, his position would have put <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, a native Austrian who left the country at age 3 with his Jewish parents, at the center of sensitive U.S.-Austrian negotiations over the illegal transfer of Western technology through <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. Several Viennese shipping agents and firms have come under scrutiny in the past decade amid <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allegations they helped the Soviets and their allies to acquire technology that was banned for export to the East. Austrian intelligence sources say they do keep a careful watch for illegal activities. Austrian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Alois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mock </PERSON>, a close friend of <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, bristled Monday when reporters suggested <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> was a hotbed of spying. `` These regrettable events are not more numerous than elsewhere,'' <PERSON> Mock </PERSON> said, allowing however that <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> is perhaps exposed because of its `` geographical position'' just an hour's ride from the Czechoslovak and Hungarian borders There are tens of thousands of Soviet and East European scientists, emigres, diplomats and other officials in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, making blanket surveillance tough. In 1981, Soviet researcher <PERSON> Arkady </PERSON> <PERSON> Belozerov </PERSON> denied reports he had spied but caused a stir when he resigned from a post at the prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Applied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analysis </ORGANIZATION>, a 17-nation project south of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> that has attracted hundreds of Soviet researchers since it was set up in 1972. A neighboring institute in the same town of <LOCATION> Laxenburg </LOCATION> was in the news the same year when <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodic </PERSON>, a Czechoslovak historian who had been granted asylum in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> as a signatory of the Charter 77 human rights appeal, suddenly disappeared. <PERSON> Hodic </PERSON> turned up in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, where state-run media said he had been working all along as a Czechoslovak agent. One of the most mysterious cases centered on <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> was that of <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shadrin </PERSON>, said to have been a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> defector turned double agent for <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Shadrin </PERSON> disappeared when he went to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> to meet two <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents in December 1975. The disappearance did not become public until July 1977, when <PERSON> Shadrin </PERSON>'s Polish-born wife said he had been kidnapped and appealed for help to get him back. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government pledged its assistance but has never disclosed <PERSON> Shadrin </PERSON>'s fate.
