<HEAD>Award-Winning Writer Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A private memorial service will be held for <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthelme </PERSON>, an award-winning modern fiction writer who died of cancer at the age of 58. <PERSON> Barthelme </PERSON> was known best for his wry humor and innovative techniques in short stories, many of which were published in The New Yorker, <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Review. <PERSON> Barthelme </PERSON> underwent successful surgery for throat cancer 17 months ago. But he became ill with a form of blood cancer while living in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> this summer and was admitted to M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> three weeks ago. He died Sunday. <PERSON> Barthelme </PERSON> also was an English professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION>. `` He was a reigning presence in the program,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>, poet and professor of English at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> was the kindest man I've known. He had a deep-bred Southern courtesy and a kind attitude towards life, personally and professionally. `` I've looked to him often as a mentor, teacher and friend.'' A former newspaperman, <PERSON> Barthelme </PERSON> wrote 15 books, including several novels and collections of short stories. His awards include a Guggenheim Fellowship in 1967, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> and Letters Award in 1972, National Book Award in 1972 and the Rea Award for the Short Story in 1988. `` His short stories were witty, funny and in an odd way deeply emotional,'' <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> said. `` He was one of the few writers who make one proud to be an <LOCATION> Ame