<HEAD>Impasse on First Day of Cambodia Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> LA </LOCATION> <LOCATION> CELLE-SAINT-CLOUD </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> told resistance leader Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> on Monday that there wo n't be any role for <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas in an interim government. At a news conference following four hours of meetings, <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> said the discussion failed to produce any results but noted more talks were scheduled Tuesday. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> said there was `` complete disagreement.'' The encounter was designed to pave way for an international conference toward ending the 10-year-old war in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by setting up a transition government. The monthlong conference begins Sunday, two months before Vietnamese troops backing <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s pro-Moscow government are to complete their withdrawal. The meeting between the two leaders at an 18th century chateau in this <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> suburb is to be expanded Tuesday to include <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> and leaders of the three-faction resistance coalition: <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sann </PERSON> of the non-Communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Khieu </PERSON> <PERSON> Samphan </PERSON>, the nominal chief of the Chinese-backed communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> since the reported resignation of former leader <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> under <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> was responsible for the deaths of hundreds of thousands of Cambodians during a three-year reign that ended with the Vietnamese invasion in December 1978. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> continues to insist on including the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> in an interim government made up of the three resistance groups and <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s government. He contends that giving the strongest of the three guerrilla groups a place in the power structure is the price of avoiding renewed civil war. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> disagrees. `` We think such a version simply signifies making the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people hostage to the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` Our position is that we are not hostages of <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> and we will not let the interests of the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people be bargained against the Pol Pottists.'' <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> took `` two steps backward'' at Monday's meeting, but he refused to call it a failure, noting discussions would continue Tuesday. Besides the future role of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, other issues on the agenda include discussion of a cease-fire and a mechanism to monitor the withdrawal of the remaining Vietnamese troops in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, estimated at up to 70,000. The Cambodian prime minister blamed the impasse on <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s insistance that as coalition president he was representing three parties In agreements reached at previous meetings, <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> represented only himself. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> said there should be only two <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> delegations to the peace talks: his government and <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kampuchea </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> has the backing of many Western nations, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the six-member Association of Southeast Asian Nations, or ASEAN. There has been growing international support for reaching a settlement that does not include the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> will attend the opening session of the international conference Sunday, and a spokeswoman reiterated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> opposition to a <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> role in an interim government. The conference is to include the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> leaders plus all five permament members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ as well as <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, and members of <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION>: <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philippins </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. As he left the chateau, <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> said the resistance coalition intended to keep fighting. The exiled prince, deposed in 1970, said that after the Sept. 30 Vietnamese withdrawal, 130,000 Vietnamese troops will remain in the country `` hidden'' in the Cambodian army. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s delegation distributed a copy of a cease-fire protocal under discussion. However, as late as Friday, <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> rejected a cease-fire so long as armed Vietnamese remain in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.
