<HEAD>Secretary Calls For `Revolution;' Analyst Says Car Still King</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> called on Monday for a `` revolution in transportation,'' possibly including high-speed rail systems, but a private analyst said the car will remain king. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> launched a series of nationwide hearings aimed at drawing up a national transportation policy for rail, highway, air and water travel. Meetings are to be held in large and small cities throughout the country through mid-September. The first one, in a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> auditorium, featured the heads of some of the country's biggest airline, railroad and automobile companies and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>, who said the whole system is a `` handyman's special.'' If the nation's system of roads, rails, waterways and airports were listed in a real estate ad, she said, it would say: `` Lots of potential, oldstyle craftsmanship with many modern conveniences, but needs work, a real fixer-upper.'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, who moderated the first session and will attend some of the other meetings, said a decision to build high-speed rail systems is one possible result of the effort. This could include trains that travel up to 300 mph, particularly between cities where air travel has reached maximum levels. `` It is time for a new revolution in transportation, and hopefully it will be a peaceful revolution,'' said <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>. In an interview prior to the meeting, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said the nation's airports, highways, bridges, waterways and mass transit systems are simply wearing out `` We're going to have to rebuild it and replace it, or we're not going to be able to rely on it anymore,'' he said. Among the most critical problems, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said, are a lack of planning for new airports and neglect of $ 80 billion worth of work needed on deteriorating bridges. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, senior research fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, told the opening session that no new system is in the wings that will revolutionize transportation within the next 25 years, so old systems have to be made more efficient. He said the fastest growth is in suburban areas as urban density continues to decline and automobile use increases. The <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> is a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> think tank that has studied several national issues, including transportation needs. `` The country has become ever more tied to its personal, on-demand, point-to-point transportation system: automobiles,'' <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said. `` Despite oil shortages and price increases, the lamentations of many environmentalists and urban planners, and multi-billion dollar federal investments in urban transit, nothing has dented the dominance of the automobile,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stempel </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and other companies are studying `` smart cars and smart highways'' that would be computerized for increased safety and efficiency. In the meantime, he said, some simple things can be done to improve road travel in many areas: traffic light coordination, improved toll road payment procedures, and clearer and brighter highway signs and markings. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is inviting citizens with ideas about how to move Americans in the 21st Century _ and about how to pay for the changes _ to attend the hearings around the country or to send written proposals to the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The transportation secretary said he does n't want the sessions to turn into a littany of complaints. `` You should n't go if you're just going to say, ` We've got gridlock, somebody ought to do something about it,' because we know that,'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said. `` These are needs and idea sessions.'' The first meeting outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> will be held in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, on Tuesday, with the focus on rural transportation issues. The last meetings will be in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on Sept. 11-12 and will deal with drug and alcohol use in the commercial transportation system and federal research and development.
