<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Revolt     07-24 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Revolt,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voter Revolt Helped Socialists but Has Conservative Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The revolt of Japanese voters against the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> gave a strong boost to the Socialists, but analysts say it was far more conservative than the result would indicate. In Sunday's election, the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> lost their majority in the upper house of Parliament for the first time since the party was formed 34 years ago. The Socialists gained 24 seats, thanks to support from women, farmers and others disgruntled with the governing party's scandals and economic policies. A record number of women candidates, 22, won their races. <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> attracted adoring crowds of women who wore pink scarves and applauded her criticism of the Liberal Democrats. When <PERSON> Sousuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> announced his resignation Monday, women reveled in their role in helping remove him. Their anger over allegations that he had kept paid mistresses hampered <PERSON> Uno </PERSON>'s efforts to restore his party's reputation after an influence-buying scandal forced predecessor <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> to quit less than two months ago. Bread-and-butter issues appeared to be even more important. `` I really believe that this was a people's revolution coming from the kitchen,'' said <PERSON> Kazuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinsaka </PERSON> of the labor-backed <ORGANIZATION> Rengo </ORGANIZATION> no Kai, a new party, who won election in <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION>. The Socialists do n't propose nationalizing industries or equalizing incomes, but talk of restoring faith in politics, repealing the new 3 percent sales tax, re-establishing protection for farmers who complain about more open import policies and improving the environment. Many women candidates campaigned not as feminists, but as `` ordinary housewives'' defending their homes against the sales tax. `` What this vote shows is that people want a return to the status quo,'' said <PERSON> Seisaburo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sato </PERSON>, a political analyst. `` It was the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> that tried to change things.'' <PERSON> Kuniko </PERSON> <PERSON> Inoguchi </PERSON> and other analysts said the economic prosperity that has characterized more than three decades of <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> government may have encouraged the discontent. `` When the economy is good, people can afford to be critical,'' <PERSON> Inoguchi </PERSON> said. `` They can afford to worry about issues of justice. `` The <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION> had modern policies but closed, premodern political practices. They were telling everybody to adjust to change _ economic liberalization and internationalization _ but did n't make an effort to change themselves.'' Although the Liberal Democrats still may have a protectionist reputation abroad, they have made major changes in the past few years, usually under foreign pressure. Beginning four years ago, the government helped the yen rise and import barriers fall enough to transform the structure of the economy and hurt important groups, such as the farmers. Economic growth, still robust, now comes more from domestic consumption and investment than exports. Japanese are richer than ever before and mamanufactured imports have increased 78 percent since 1985. Protection of agriculture is being chipped away. A tax reform package many experts consider economically sound but clumsily introduced has given salaried workers more money to spend and may help bring <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economy more in line with those of its trading partners. The sales tax part has outraged housewives, however. Women seek change in several areas. They have joined the labor force in record numbers, helped by an equal opportunity law, but often in poorly paid part-time jobs. Affluence has meant free time and more education, but women are angered by lingering discrimination exemplified by Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Hisao </PERSON> <PERSON> Horinouchi </PERSON>'s recent remark that they are `` useless in politics.''
</TEXT>
