<HEAD>Bush Says U.S. Needs Maximum Flexibility in Arms Control Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Bill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lobbied senators Monday to support his $ 295 billion defense budget, saying the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> needs `` maximum flexibility'' in arms control negotiations. The president called a bipartisan group of senators to the White House for a pep talk as lawmakers prepared for congressional floor action on military spending measures. Although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said defense programs are `` complicated, expensive,'' he urged full funding for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s fiscal program. Already, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> has made some `` important cuts'' in defense, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, praised <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> for making tough choices in killing six or seven programs The committee has `` been willing to bite a part of that bullet, too,'' he said, adding: `` We hope the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will stick with us because we have basically backed the <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> budget.'' Among the potential targets of congressional budget-cutters are the B-2 bomber, known as the stealth, the Strategic Defense Initiative, or Star Wars, and how much money to give the rail-mobile MX missiles or the single-warhead Midgetman. The expensive B-2 _ each plane is expected to cost more than $ 500 million _ has been criticized by some lawmakers. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called the radar-evading plane a `` revolutionary technology'' that is vital to the nation's defense. He said he could justify the B-2 expense because `` when you look at the full defense program, I want to have maximum flexibility as we have arms control negotiations.'' The administration's defense outline calls for 132 bombers at a cost of $ 70.2 billion. For fiscal 1990, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to spend $ 4.7 billion, but the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has already cut $ 800 million from the program. Last week, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made his pitch to members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he is hopeful the administration will get money for three bombers in the current round. The plane made its first flight last week in <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` We put fences around the B-2,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. `` We want to make sure that the plane performs as advertised, both in terms of its flying ability and also in terms of its stealth characteristics, which are crucial.'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> also said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel supports complete research and development of the V-22, known as the Osprey, but it wants to withhold advanced procurement money until it is determined the tilt-rotor aircraft can be used commercially. The senators want `` to see if someone other than the taxpayer is going to put up some money,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said.
