<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Effect of Mexican Deal on Third World Still Unclear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The general agreement between <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and its creditor banks offers a glimmer of hope to the debt-strapped Third World, but the success of the plan hinges on how far the banks are ultimately willing to go, government officials and private bankers said Monday. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, which provided a final push over the weekend to get the agreement, hailed the package as a landmark success for its debt-reduction initiative, unveiled by Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> on March 10. However, the banks that will implement the plan were more reserved in their enthusiasm, with many contending that it was too soon to say how much debt relief they will provide to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> because they were still examining the fine print of the agreement. `` At the moment, we're exploring our options,'' <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> <PERSON> Seitel </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said in a typical comment. `` We're looking at the entire -LRB- Third World -RRB- debt package.'' The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration hopes to use the Mexican agreement to set a precedent that will facilitate debt relief in other countries, with <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> considered the two leading candidates to follow <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s lead. The administration has made debt reduction a key component of its foreign policy, believing that the only way to insure the survival of emerging democracies in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is to find a way to reverse the decade-long slide in living standards caused by the crushing $ 1.3 trillion Third World debt burden. The <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan for debt relief seeks to slash this debt by establishing incentives to get commerical banks to voluntarily forgive a portion of the loans. However, banking analysts said it was unclear whether the incentives being offered in the Mexican package were sufficient to trigger a substantial writedown of the debt. In the case of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the debt-reduction package provides the commercial banks with three options. On the debt-relief side, the banks can cut 35 percent off the face value of the current loans or they can agree to reduce interest rates to 6.25 percent, down from about 10 percent currently. Banks also have the option of simply providing new loans. The administration estimated that the various options could save <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> about $ 1.5 billion annually off the $ 5 billion to $ 5.5 billion it must pay to service its $ 54 billion in commercial bank debt. However, the administration stressed that this was a rough estimate and would vary depending on individual decisions made by the 500 commercial banks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that hold the Mexican debt. Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and a leading congressional expert on Third World debt, said that the Mexican agreement appeared seriously flawed because it did not provide enough incentives for banks to opt for the two debt-reduction options rather than simply piling on new debt. `` A lot of the banks, without the necessary carrots or sticks, are going to stick with the familiar -LRB- approach of supplying -RRB- new money to pay old debt,'' <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> said that approach has proven to be a disaster over the last seven years. Since 1982, when the debt crisis first erupted, Third World debt has more than doubled from $ 600 billion to $ 1.3 trillion. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> LaFalce </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> agreement did not represent any `` long-lasting breakthrough in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s debt situation.'' He said that, while the amount of debt-reduction was likely to be small, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> would benefit in the next couple of years with an infusion of money to get its economy started again. <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON>, an economist with <PERSON> DRI-McGraw </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, said that the administration apparently failed to get as many concessions as it could from the commercial banks because they were so anxious to get an agreement. `` It looks like they desperately wanted to do a deal and get something signed to prove that their debt strategy could work,'' she said. `` It is a surface agreement that allows the administration to claim a success but it leaves a lot of unanswered questions.'' The administration had hoped that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would be able to present a completed Mexican package during the seven-nation economic summit last week in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. When that deadline was missed, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> stepped up his lobbying efforts. He brought the bankers and Mexican negotiators to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> over the weekend for meetings at the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, which were also attended by <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>. After two days of discussions at the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, final agreement was reached late Sunday, in time for Mexican President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> to announce the breakthrough during a televised broadcast, saying the proposal would answer the `` the cry of Mexicans to return to growth.''
</TEXT>
