<HEAD>Sri Lanka Lifts Censorship Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government Monday lifted 3-week-old censorship restrictions on reporting ethnic violence but told journalists to censor themselves. Also Monday, authorities halted a rally by about 600 <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks who were demanding the expulsion of Indian peacekeeping troops. No violence was reported. The monks' organization, which claims to represent 25,000 members, said it is prepared to join an armed struggle to oust the Indian forces. Monk are an important political force in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. The government's announcement that censorship was being lifted came 26 hours after the slaying of its chief censor, <PERSON> Themis </PERSON> <PERSON> Guruge </PERSON>. He was shot to death Sunday while walking near his home. Government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, blamed the slaying of <LOCATION> Guruge </LOCATION>, who also headed state-run radio, on Sinhalese extremists. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> informed local newspaper editors that censorship had been lifted, but he also warned them: `` Be more responsible and maintain self-censorship, especially on subversive activities and the Indian issue.'' The censorship had taken heavy criticism from both government and opposition lawmakers. The July 6 announcement of censorship on domestic and foreign press coincided with worsening ethnic violence and a deepening dispute with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> has demanded that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> pull out 40,000 soldiers deployed as a peacekeeping force. President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> has denounced the Indian military presence in his nation as a threat to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s sovereignty and demanded a pullout by the end of July. Indian peacekeepers arrived in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> two years ago at the invitation of <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s predecessor, President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has long said it does not intend to keep its force here indefinitely, but Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> has said a premature withdrawal would lead to even more bloodshed. More than 15,000 people have been killed in ethnic violence that started with a separatist revolt by ethnic Tamil guerrillas in 1983. About 11,000 people have died in the Tamil insurrection, including 1,000 Indian soldiers. According to the government, Sinhalese extremists killed 4,000 people _ mostly Sinhalese government officials and supporters _ in a backlash against what they perceived as excessive concessions to the Tamils. The militant Sinhalese have been led by the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. During censorship, most references to the front or to Sinhalese radicals were removed from news stories. Tamils, who make up about 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, say they are discriminated against by Sinhalese. The majority Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the population, dominating the government and military. During their rally, the saffron-robed monks were defying a ban on such protests. They pushed past a line of police and sat on the narrow lane outside the Sri Mahabodhi Temple in the capital, <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Earlier, their <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bhikkhu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement saying thousands of monks were prepared to join an armed struggle to preserve Sri Lankan sovereignty from what it called `` the Indian army of invasion.'' Before the rally, a 25-year old monk who declined to give his name told a news conference in the temple compound that the monks' federation had decided to join militant Sinhalese extremists and student groups in opposing the government and the presence of Indian peacekeepers `` We do not believe the Indian army would go back on just a request,'' the monk said. `` We believe that we have to take further action, and we are prepared to do it.'' Asked if the monks condoned violence, he said: `` If an armed struggle is demanded to gain the freedom of the people, the <LOCATION> Bhikku </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Federation </LOCATION> does approve and will participate in it.''
