<HEAD>Justice Department Backs Higher Fines for Corporate Crimes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it supported a ten-fold increase in the maximum fine for criminal antitrust violations by corporations to $ 10 million. The department, noting it is conducting more than 150 grand jury investigations of alleged criminal antitrust violations, said an increase was needed to deter price fixing, bid rigging and unlawful attempts by corporations to control the market on certain products. Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said in a statement that he supported legislation pending in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that would increase the maximum fine from $ 1 million to $ 10 million for corporate antitrust violations. `` This increase in penalties will send a strong signal to those who intend to defraud American consumers or the federal government through criminal antitrust conspiracies that the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> takes their criminal conduct most seriously and will see that they are appropriately punished,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. He issued the statement on the eve of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hearing on antitrust issues. The proposal to increase the maximum corporate fine was contained in legislation sponsored by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>, R-S.C. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rill </PERSON>, the new assistant attorney general in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> ` santitrust division, is scheduled to testify at Tuesday's <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> noted in a statement that `` it has been 15 years since criminal fines for coprorate antitrust offenders were raised, and a sizeable increase in fines now is a good way to underscore that this criminal activity will not be tolerated.'' The fines apply to criminal antitrust violations such as price fixing and bid rigging, which <PERSON> Rill </PERSON> noted is `` undertaken purely to defraud its victims and has no possible economic justification.'' <PERSON> Rill </PERSON>, noting that the antitrust division is conducting more than 150 grand jury investigations of suspected criminal violations, said current fines `` do not appear to be adequately deterring this unlawful conduct.''
