<HEAD>China Airs Official Version of Democracy Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State-run TV on Monday broadcast the government's first documentary account of the events leading up to its bloody suppression of pro-democracy protests in early June The first hour of the four-part series, `` A Test of Blood and Fire,'' was as remarkable for what it left out as for what it included. It did n't show the students singing the national anthem, which they did constantly. It also did n't show posters attacking corruption and nepotism, or banners proclaiming the protesters' love for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Footage shown in the program, unlike earlier official reports, did show Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> hanging in effigy and banners mocking senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>. In the first two weeks after the crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators June 3-4 that left hundreds or perhaps thousands dead, state-run TV repeatedly showed angry crowds stoning troops and setting army vehicles on fire. Monday's was the first official documentary account of the events leading up to June 3 that purported to put the student movement into perspective. Some events in the documentary were shown out of sequence, apparently to strengthen the government's argument that the student marches were instigated by anti-communist intellectuals. Dissident intellectuals, who remained on the sidelines until the last stages of the protests, were portrayed as speaking to students much earlier than they did. Apparently to support government claims that the student-led protests were orchestrated many months in advance by dissidents such as <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON>, the program began by showing students discussing democratic reforms at forums last winter. <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> and his wife, physics professor <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuxian </PERSON>, were shown at that time speaking to the students. <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> and <PERSON> Li </PERSON> did not appear in public support of the later protests sparked by the death of former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON> in mid-April. After the crackdown, however, they sought refuge in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The Chinese government has demanded they be handed over for arrest. Monday's TV program repeatedly accused <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s successor as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> head, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, of contributing to the `` turmoil'' of the widespread demonstrations. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, who was ousted following the crackdown on dissent, has been accused of supporting the student protests and opposing other party leaders who wanted to quash them. Public criticism of <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> has mounted steadily since his June 24 ouster from his party posts. Several reports of comments <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> allegedly made at closed meetings have been cited to prove his softness on Western-style liberalism, which the government blames for the student movement. An editorial Monday in the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> accused <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> of supporting `` words and deeds that vilified Marxism'' and spreading non-Marxist theories. It did not give any specifics.
