<HEAD>GAO Says Pentagon Fails to Test Planes for Impacts with Birds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite losing nine military aircraft and six crew members to bird collisions over a five-year period, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> still fails to test its planes to see whether they can withstand such impacts, congressional investigators said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, an investigating agency for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, reported that from 1983 through 1987 more than 16,000 collisions occurred. While most caused only minor damage, nine planes _ including a $ 250 million B-1B bomber _ crashed after colliding with birds. Losses for the period totaled $ 318 million. `` If our military aircraft are not ready for birds, how can they be ready for combat?'' asked Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>, D-Mich., who requested the study for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which he heads `` The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> did not ask us for a comment and we have n't even seen it,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bodanyi </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, when asked for reaction to the report. The report's release coincided with opening of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> consideration of the future of the new-generation B-2 stealth bomber, at $ 530 million each the most expensive airplane ever built. `` With more expensive aircraft coming into use, such as the B-1B and B-2, the value of these losses could become more significant,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The investigators found that specifications are inconsistent for the ability of airplanes and engines to withstand bird collisions. Where there are specifications for engines, the testing does not accurately reflect the sizes and numbers of birds normally sucked into jet engines, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The military agency has no testing program to see how well airframes _ the plane's body and wings, particularly leading edges _ stand up to bird collisions, investigators said. The report suggested requiring in government contracts that adequate testing be done, and having the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> enforce that requirement, as a way to reduce unnecessary costs.
