ople. He said both events showed the dangers faced by democracy movements around the world. <PERSON> Shi </PERSON>, the senior <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> delegate, stood up about halfway through the speech, as soon as <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> made the remarks about <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. He was quickly followed by the second delegate, <PERSON> Niu </PERSON> <PERSON> Qiang </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> and Disarmament. Two other Chinese delegates kept their seats in another part of the room, but it was unclear whether they did so deliberately or failed to notice the departure of <PERSON> Shi </PERSON> and Niu. Despite the incident, <PERSON> Shi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Niu </PERSON> said they planned to attend the rest of the conference, which will explore ways to convert warmer East-West relations into practical agreements on arms control and verification. <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Innas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, a nuclear physicist from <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s confrontation with the Chinese did not dampen the optimism of most delegates, who believe the time is ripe for arms accords. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> urged the delegates to take advantage of the Soviet-American rapprochement. `` It may be a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the unsuccessful <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate for president.
