<HEAD>Finland's Leading Opera Star Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials and supporters of the new National Opera were reeling Monday from the death of <PERSON> Martti </PERSON> <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON>, the country's leading opera star, who had agreed to take over as director. The 54-year-old singer, whose bass voice had boomed through opera houses from <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scala </ORGANIZATION> to the Metropolitan, died Saturday. One colleague on Monday called him `` the father figure of Finnish opera.'' News reports said <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> died during the wedding dance of his youngest daughter on his farm in <LOCATION> Juva </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Savonlinna </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>. They indicated he died of a heart attack. His family refused to discuss the cause of death or funeral arrangements. Two months before his death, <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> agreed to become director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> in 1992 after the opera house is finished. <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> said his aim would be to make the Finnish opera `` on a par with the best in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Alfons </PERSON> <PERSON> Almi </PERSON>, a leading figure behind the plan to build a new opera, said <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> was the only real candidate for director. `` The directorship was tailor-made for <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON>. He is irreplaceable,'' <PERSON> Almi </PERSON> said in a newspaper interview Monday. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON>, a member of the committee to select a new director, described <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON>'s death as a `` catastrophe'' for the National Opera. `` It will be very difficult to find a suitable new director,'' <PERSON> Lindberg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON>, born Feb. 4, 1935, began his international singing career after winning a contest in <LOCATION> Vaasa </LOCATION>, west <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, in 1960. He had trained to be a school teacher and singing was just a hobby. He then studied singing in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>. After a breakthrough at the <PERSON> Bayreuth </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> festival, he was signed by the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Deutsche Opera. During his career, <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> performed more abroad than in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>. In addition to the Metropolitan Opera of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Scala </PERSON>, his stages have included the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Bolshoi and the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> National Opera. He was said to have sung all the major opera roles for bass voices. He was particularly acclaimed for his interpretation of the title role of <LOCATION> Mussorgsky </LOCATION>'s opera `` <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Godunov </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> was artistic director of the annual Savonlinna Opera Festival from 1972 to 1979. He elevated the festival to a major international opera event. <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> <PERSON> Gronroos </PERSON>, current artistic director of the festival, said <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON>'s `` uncompromising nature was precisely the reason why he was able to create such great art.'' `` In <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON>, we have lost a visionary, the father figure of Finnish opera,'' <PERSON> Gronroos </PERSON> said. Not long before he died, <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> was asked about his reputed stubborn streak. `` Nobody can ever force me to do anything, but I am always prepared to negotiate,'' he said. When not working, <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> spent much of his time at his summer retreat in <LOCATION> Juva </LOCATION>, where he tended a flock of 100 sheep. <PERSON> Talvela </PERSON> is survived by his wife of 32 years, <PERSON> Annukka </PERSON>, and by three adult children.
