<HEAD>Blasts Damage Army Recruiting Station, Post Office in Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pipe bombs blasted an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> recruiting station and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> post office Monday, authorities said. A telephone caller claimed the two bombs were planted by a pro-independence group. There were no reports of injuries from the blasts, which came on the eve of Puerto Rico Constitution Day. The holiday celebrates the 37-year-old Constitution that made the island a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commonwealth. A series of similar bomb attacks have struck the island in recent months. Monday's caller told a radio station the bombs were placed by the Puerto Rican Revolutionary Forces, a little-known group. Police could not confirm the authenticity of the call. The male caller, who did not give his name, said the bombing was to protest military bases in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> and its Commonwealth status. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> provides defense for <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, and its only military bases are American. The Pentagon has 3,350 active servicemen on the island, including 2,000 at the <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roads </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> on the west coast. Police said the Monday's bombs went off at 2 a.m. at the <ORGANIZATION> Plaza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shopping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> about 10 miles east of metropolitan <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>. They caused `` considerable'' damage to the Army recruiting office, the post office and several public telephones, all on the interior of the shopping center, police said. They also damaged the administrative offices of the Pueblo Supermarket, which faces the parking lot. Police and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents were investigating. Two bombs went off last week at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> post offices in <LOCATION> Coamo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guayama </LOCATION>, municipalities in the island's interior. No injuries were reported. In June, the <ORGANIZATION> Borinquen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, also known as the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Macheteros </LOCATION> or machete-wielders, claimed responsibility for a bomb that caused heavy damage but no injuries at an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> recruiting station and a branch of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bayamon </LOCATION>. The town is about 15 miles northwest of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Borinquen </PERSON> was <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s name before the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> conquest of the island in the 16th century. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> ceded the island to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1898. Similar explosions, with no injuries and only minor damage, occurred in June at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs office in the southern city of <LOCATION> Ponce </LOCATION> and at a <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> branch in <LOCATION> Caguas </LOCATION>, about 20 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>. No group claimed responsibility for those blasts. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Macheteros </LOCATION> is a militant pro-independence group that has been relatively inactive in recent years. During the 1970s, it blew up five <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> fighter jets worth $ 47 million and ambushed a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vehicle, killing two sailors and injuring 10. Sixteen suspected members were charged in the $ 7 million robbery of a <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> depot in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, in 1983. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> charges that the Macheteros intended to use the money to pay for their campaign to gain independence for <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>.
