<FIRST>r w AM-AgricultureBudget     07-24 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agriculture Budget,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commodity Spending Less Than Anticipated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal spending on major commodity programs is down from what administration budget analysts forecast in January, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analysis showed Monday. Total outlays in the fiscal year that began Oct. 1 are now projected at less than $ 13.5 billion, about $ 360 million below the January prediction. Programs include payments to farmers for participating in annual crop programs. In the case of major crops, such as wheat, corn and cotton, the programs provide price supports and other benefits in return for taking land out of production. But some other commodities also are covered, including price support operations for soybeans, peanuts, tobacco, honey, sugar, dairy products and wool. Outlays for corn and other feed grains in 1989 were indicated in January at about $ 3.04 billion. The new `` mid-session review'' raised the estimate to $ 4.17 billion. At the same time, spending for wheat, rice and upland cotton programs was reduced by more than $ 1.3 billion from the January forecast. Allowing for adjustments in other programs administered by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, total spending for the various agricultural commodities was reduced a net of $ 86 million to less than $ 7.03 billion for this fiscal year. Other CCC spending, including $ 3.75 billion for aid to farmers who suffered severe losses from the 1988 drought, put the fiscal 1989 total at just under $ 13.5 billion, compared with the January estimate of more than $ 13.8 billion. Looking at 1990, the report said total CCC spending could drop to just over $ 11.3 billion, down $ 231 million from what was projected in January. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> budget analyst, said the boost in feed-grain outlays from the level initially projected was a result of new quarterly grain inventory figures in January. Those showed more feed grain on hand than had been indicated previously. It was this larger inventory that `` we did not take into account when we did the budget'' that was published by the out-going <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration Jan. 9 and later adopted by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, he said. <PERSON> Steele </PERSON> said in an interview that the Jan. 9 projections were based on supply-and demand readings last November. The new review took into consideration the grain figures that were issued Jan. 13. Looking at fiscal 1990, which will begin Oct. 1, the new report showed total CCC outlays at less than $ 11.4 billion, down about $ 231 million from what had been projected in January. Spending on feed grains in 1989-90 was indicated at nearly $ 7.07 billion, up from the $ 5.56 billion projected in January. Declines from the January projections were shown for wheat, rice and cotton.
</TEXT>
