<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The governors of eight <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states met with congressional environmental leaders Monday and then signed a broadly worded agreement to work for clean oceans. Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass., acknowledged that the document, which was passed from governor to governor while homestate television cameras rolled, `` probably will not take its place between the <ORGANIZATION> Magna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carta </ORGANIZATION> and the Mayflower Compact. But he joined other participants at a news conference following the closed meeting in saying the agreement was a symbolic achievement that signaled the governors were determined to work among themselves and with federal officials to solve environmental problems. Standing behind <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, last year's Democratic presidential nominee, <PERSON> Studds </PERSON> said it will take billions of dollars just to clean up <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> alone and that the main measure of success for the governors' `` coastal agenda'' will be `` the number of dollars we are able to put behind them. The bipartisan meeting, attended by about a dozen members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, was arranged by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON>, also a Democrat. The governors of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> also attended the ceremony. The document specifically did not endorse any of the many pieces of federal legislation pending on environmental issues and purposely was worded vaguely enough to ensure unanimous support. For example, the first section of the five-part plan _ `` Create an Environmental Ethic'' _ says `` Federal and state policies must reflect the need for strengthened environmental protection'' and `` Education and public participation must be strenghtened to show how everyone can participate in the solution to coastal pollution problems.'' The document also called for strengthening research and monitoring of coastal waters; reducing coastal nutrient and toxic pollution; protection of marine and coastal sediment quality; and expansion of government authority for oil spill prevention and response. `` This is the beginning,'' <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON> of the meeting. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., said the most important aspect of the agreement was its call for creation of an environmental ethic because significant progress will not be made `` until the ethic becomes strong enough for force funding. Pressed to estimate how much money would be needed to accomplish the goals of the group, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said, `` There is no single overall figure and I think it is a mistake to view it in the context of those kind of questions.'' He emphasized that there was no attempt to get the group to agree on specific legislation and added: `` I think it is very significant that we got started and got the agreement that we did.''
