<HEAD>Secretary Calls For `Revolution;' Analyst Says Car Still King</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> called on Monday for a `` revolution in transportation,'' possibly including high-speed rail systems, but a private analyst said the car will remain king. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> launched a series of nationwide hearings aimed at drawing up a national transportation policy for rail, highway, air and water travel. Meetings are to be held in large and small cities throughout the country through mid-September. The first one, in a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> auditorium, featured the heads of some of the country's biggest airline, railroad and automobile companies and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>, who said the whole system is a `` handyman's special.'' If the nation's system of roads, rails, waterways and airports were listed in a real estate ad, she said, it would say: `` Lots of potential, oldstyle craftsmanship with many modern conveniences, but needs work, a real fixer-upper.'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, who moderated the first session and will attend some of the other meetings, said a decision to build high-speed rail systems is one possible result of the effort. This could include trains that travel up to 300 mph, particularly between cities where air travel has reached maximum levels. `` It is time for a new revolution in transportation, and hopefully it will be a peaceful revolution,'' said <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>. In an interview prior to the meeting, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said the nation's airports, highways, bridges, waterways and mass transit systems are simply wearing out `` We're going to have to rebuild it and replace it, or we're not going to be able to rely on it anymore,'' he said. Among the most critical problems, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said, are a lack of planning for new airports and neglect of $ 80 billion worth of work needed on deteriorating bridges. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSO