a <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> project for which <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> had lobbied was on her list for funding under the agency's Section 8 Moderate Rehabilitation program. Also on Ms. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>'s approval list for the date April 7, 1987, according to the notes released by the subcommittee, were 200 units for `` <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> _ <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON> is a former <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senator who as an attorney has lobbied <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> on behalf of developers. Ms. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> is a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney who since leaving <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 has had extensive dealings with the agency. She said that in the summer of 1985 while her law firm was representing a client in HUD-related matters, she was shown a draft of a letter <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> was preparing to send to <ORGANIZATION> DRG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a major lender in a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> coinsurance program that had been placed on probation because of numerous problems with its loan-approval practices. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> criticized the firm for most of a nine-page letter but in the next-to-last paragraph announced he was lifting restrictions <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> had placed on the company. At the time, DRG was on <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> probation and had to have all its loans approved in advance. Ms. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s client was applying to DRG for financing and its project was stalled because <ORGANIZATION> DRG </ORGANIZATION> had to get <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> approval of the loan. Ms. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said she made comments about the draft letter but that it was not changed to reflect her position. And she disputed contentions that she should not have been shown the document before it was made public, saying there frequently was such `` give and take about the language'' between <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials and representatives of major firms doing business with the agency. Subcommittee member, however, did not accept her justification. `` I think you are being evasive,'' <PERSON> Shays </PERSON> said after Ms. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said she could not respond in detail to his question about Ms. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>'s role in a later decision involving DRG, this one an ultimately unsuccessful attempt to help a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> development on which <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> coinsured a mortgage that was issued at several times the property's value. The exchanges with <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> were at times humorous. When <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> told Rep. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass., that he had great respect for the congressman and his `` knack'' for crafting catchy phrases, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> responded: `` Why do I feel I should hold on to my wallet at this moment, Mr <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>?''
