<HEAD>Walesa Will Confer with Jaruzelski</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with official announcement of meeting,
Jaruzelski consulting with other parties. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> will meet with new President <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> to discuss how the new government should be formed, the state-run news agency said Monday. The meeting in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> on Tuesday will be the first since the army general and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> first secretary was narrowly elected president by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on July 19. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> began consultations with leaders of the nation's political and social forces Monday, meeting the chairmen of two parties allied with his own <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency said <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> is in the process of deciding who to nominate as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s next prime minister and has urged Solidarity to join the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in a coalition government. Solidarity lawmakers, who as the result of partly democratic elections in June control the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and account for 35 percent of the parliament's lower house, are deeply divided over whether to enter into such a coalition. On Thursday, Solidarity lawmakers discussed whether to share the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> with party ministers or whether to demand all the Cabinet seats including the prime minister's post but excluding control of the army and police. They also considered whether to stay entirely out of the government and function solely as a parliamentary opposition. The debate was to resume this week. The <ORGANIZATION> Walesa-Jaruzelski </ORGANIZATION> meeting, confirmed by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Krzysztof </PERSON> <PERSON> Pusz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, was expected to give both leaders a chance to exchange views on how the next government should be formed. On Monday, <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> met with chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the two allied parties that form the Communist coalition in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said. The new president also will meet with chairmen of the official <ORGANIZATION> OPZZ </ORGANIZATION> union, other government-sanctioned groups and the independent farmers union, Rural Solidarity, the agency said. The state news agency announced that <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> deputies in the lower house would confer Tuesday. Solidarity lawmakers will hold their caucus Wednesday.
