<HEAD>Exiled Prince Calls for Restoration of Monarchy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The heir to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s abolished throne has called for the restoration of the monarchy as a way to overcome the economic and political problems in this Communist-ruled country. `` I hope that my country will reform politically so that the ruling party competes in elections with the full freedom of the people to decide,'' said Crown Prince <PERSON> Aleksandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Karadjordjevic </PERSON> in an interview published in the current issue of Start magazine in <LOCATION> Zagreb </LOCATION>. `` If I ever go to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> it will be to live there and to contribute to its development,'' said <PERSON> Aleksandar </PERSON> who has never been in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. The interview was held in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Aleksandar </PERSON> lives. His father, <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, fled <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> in 1941 during the Nazi invasion and spent the war years in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Aleksandar </PERSON> was born in 1945. The king and other members of the royal family were barred from returning when the monarchy was abolished and a single-party republic proclaimed in 1945. <PERSON> Aleksandar </PERSON> served as an officer in the British army and is now a succesful businessman. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is struggling with soaring inflation, unemployment, ethnic strife between its various nationalities and divisions within the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership.
