<HEAD>Cemeteries Full after 14 Years of Civil War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE with report Lebanese Shiite factions
pledge to end feud.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of residents fled from artillery duels in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> Monday, some taking their dead with them amid reports that 14 years of civil war have filled <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s cemeteries to capacity The ghost-town atmosphere also spawned the first major bank robbery in two years. `` I have never seen <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in such sadness,'' said one resident. `` It is as if the whole of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> is preparing for a funeral.'' Syrian gunners killed an elderly Greek Orthodox priest and wounded three other civilians in a bombardment of Christian east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and the shore north of the capital, said a police spokesman. Christian artillery blasted Syrian batteries along west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s seafront, but all shells landed offshore and there were no casualties, said the spokesman He also said six people drowned this weekend trying to get water from wells in Moslem districts of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, which has been without water for a week. The latest casualties raised the toll to 453 dead and 1,859 injured since the confrontation erupted March 8 between Lebanese army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s mostly Christian troops and Moslem Syrian army soldiers. The shelling went on sporadically through the night but was less intense than the weekend bombardment, which underscored <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s attempt to break <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s naval and land blockades imposed March 14 against the 310-square-mile Christian enclave <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> has blockaded illegal ports operated by Moslem militias. Police said 700,000 of the city's 1.5 million residents have fled since March, with a quarter-million streaming out in recent days. In west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elias </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, masked gunmen stormed into the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beirut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, locked employees and clients in one room and escaped with an estimated $ 40,000, said the police spokesman. Bank robberies proliferated during the lawless period between 1984 and 1987 when feuding Moslem militias fought for control of west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Robberies declined after <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> sent troops to restore order. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> keeps 40,000 troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate. Lately, caskets have been piling up around the city's cemeteries, and ambulances and hearses were seen leaving <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on Monday taking the dead to other parts of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> for burial `` Cemeteries in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, the city of death, have no room left for new graves,'' <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s conservative Ad-Diyar newspaper said Monday. It quoted an unidentified cemetery caretaker as saying: `` Graves are full. The new fatalities will have to remain out in the open because there is no burial space left.'' More than 150,000 people have been killed since the civil war broke out in 1975, mostly in and around <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` We're packed to the brim,'' said a Greek Orthodox priest at west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Saint <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>'s church, whose courtyard houses the biggest Christian cemetery in the Moslem sector. `` We have to work out a system to cope, but I do n't know how.'' <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s vast public beaches were deserted Monday and the only people on the streets searched for water. `` Water vendors are making a killing,'' according to <PERSON> Zuheir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullah </PERSON>, a janitor who said he had just invested his savings of $ 750 buying 200 gallons of water, half of which he plans to sell. Vendors are selling water for about $ 10 a gallon. In <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s rival Shiite Moslem factions pledged in a joint communique issued in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> to end their 15-month-old feud, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. An estimated 560 people have been killed in fighting between the Syrian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militia and pro-Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> that erupted in early July following a five-month lull. The communique was published Monday, one day after leaders of both Shiite factions ended a two-week visit to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> report monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. Amal and <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> have been fighting to dominate <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 1.2 million Shiites.
