<HEAD>Soviet Eskimos Take Part in Arctic Gathering for First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Arctic Eskimos from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> in the west to <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> in the east met in <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> on Monday to discuss common cultural and ecological problems. It was the first time a Soviet delegation attended a general assembly of the <ORGANIZATION> Inuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circumpolar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, a non-governmental umbrella organization for Inuit, or Eskimos, from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. About 450 Inuit were expected take part in the <LOCATION> west </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> township of <LOCATION> Sisimuit </LOCATION>. A 10-man delegation, which is attending as an observer, says it represents native Siberians known as Yuit. `` Even though President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s perestroika has reached areas of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> where the 1,600 Yuit live, there are many problems we would like to discuss with the <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION>,'' delegation leader <PERSON> Nadesjda </PERSON> <PERSON> Utke </PERSON> said during a stopover in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>. `` We want to exchange experiences in maintaining traditional hunting and implements, educational materials and greater participation by the local people in decision-making,'' she said. The fifth general assembly was being held under the motto `` A Celebration of Inuit Unity,'' to mark the first Soviet participation. It was opened by the current Conference President, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Topics for discussion during the five-day gathering included environment and renewable resources, promotion of Inuit rights internationally and transboundry pollution of the Arctic. A series of workshops were set up to study and report back on such specialized topics as <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> peace and security, whaling, the `` anti-harvesting'' conservation movement's impact on traditional hunting, Inuit culture, land use and costal zone management. About 40,000 Inuit live in <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, 28,000 in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and 11,000 in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The Soviet Inuits comprise a small part of the 150,000 natives of the Siberian north. <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, the world's biggest island and a former colony of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, this summer celebrates its tenth year with homerule-style local government.
