<HEAD>Ruling Party Opens National Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s ruling party, opened its national congress Monday with strong hints of moving away from Marxist ideology toward a market-oriented economy. The eight-day party congress also is expected to debate a plan by President <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> calling for negotiation between the government and rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Mozambique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION>, commonly called <ORGANIZATION> Renamo </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION>, the Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mozambique </ORGANIZATION>, has ruled the nation in southeastern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975. The rebel war, combined with mismanagement and a weak infrastructure left by the <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION>, has made <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> one of the world's poorest countries. In his opening address, <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> appeared to hint at better relations with businessmen and others who have had little influence in the past. `` Since our essential task is to combat the destabilization of which the country is a target, all Mozambican classes and social strata are equally involved in the project'' of rebuilding the country, he declared. Among changes to be considered are admission of property owners, businessmen, shop owners and the religious faithful to Frelimo membership. <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> said, however, that religious believers would have to `` accept that the implementation of the party program is no less important'' than their beliefs. The country has a mixture of Christians, Moslems and animists. Another proposed change would lift restrictions on the number of workers who can be employed by farmers belonging to <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION>, which the official news agency AIM said `` is justified by the need to increase food production and for party members to lead this drive.'' It added, however, that a party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> report to be discussed at the congress `` makes clear its preference for party members to work in cooperatives.'' Vigorous debate is expected on economic policy and government efforts to end the war, which has cost hundreds of thousands of lives and half the country's 14.7 million people wholly or partly dependent on food aid. The government has been moving to end central control of the economy since 1983. It has met conditions set by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and has experienced modest growth in recent years after a decade of decline.
