<HEAD>Ship Bottom Buckling Concerns Raised Over Impact On Salvageability</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Exxon Pullout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Underwater sections of the hull of the tanker <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION>, ripped open on a reef that caused the nation's worst oil spill, have increasingly buckled and loosened, officials said Monday. `` I want to stress and emphasize we are not yet in a critical situation,'' <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Solberg </PERSON> said. `` We're still optimistic the ship will be able to come in -LRB- for repairs -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Solberg </PERSON> said the ship remains seaworthy, but its fate increasingly is at the mercy of weather and ocean conditions as it waits off <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> to be declared free of environmental and navigational hazards. The Valdez spilled nearly 11 million gallons of crude into <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s wildlife-rich Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> on March 24 after it went off course and rammed its hull across <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION>. Preliminary repairs were made before the ship was towed 2,500 miles to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> for repairs in drydock, but during the voyage huge sections of underwater hull plating pulled away and dangled beneath the hull. Working four to six miles off <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clemente </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, divers through Monday had cut away five of seven jagged steel plates. They began the interim repairs Friday and expect to take three to four more days to finish. The dangling plates must be removed so the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> can navigate <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> shallows en route to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN