<HEAD>Exxon Says Fall Pullout Non-Negotiable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State environmental officials said Monday they are unhappy with <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s plan to withdraw its oil spill cleanup forces from Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> by mid-September, but the company says the pullout is not negotiable. `` We've been saying all along we would operate until about Sept. 15 when we have to shut down because of the weather,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON>. `` None of that has changed. `` Generally Sept. 15 is an average date. Sometimes bad weather starts before that; sometimes after that.'' A July 19 memo from <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s general manager in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, to company officials indicates <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> is adamant about a mid-September pullout. He said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> will conduct no winter cleanup operations because of safety and operational reasons and the company's only commitment for next spring is to survey the shorelines. `` These are not negotiable points,'' he wrote in the memo, a copy of which was provided to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The memo was dated the day before Exxon President <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' testimony to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ocean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, Science and <ORGANIZATION> Transportion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> He reluctantly committed the company to resuming operations next year if more work needs to be done. But <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Provant </PERSON>, on-scene oil spill coordinator for the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION>, said his agency wants <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> to leave a contingency force behind to deal with oil that may wash off beaches and cause problems during the winter. `` We're not asking them to do any beach cleaning or anything like that in the winter,'' he said. An army of 11,000 people, 1,000 vessels and more than 70 aircraft has been trying to clean beaches stained by the nation's largest oil spill The Exxon Valdez rammed <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> on March 24, spilling about 11 million gallons of crude oil into the sound's pristine waters `` You ca n't work up to the last day and pull them all out,'' <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON> said. `` We're working on a plan that gets them out by Sept. 15. That's the average date of when the winter storms set in and you can no longer operate out there.'' He said studies to determine the exact day the last <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> workers would be withdrawn should be completed in about two weeks. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> on Monday announced that the cleanup costs stemming from the spill had reduced its second-quarter profit by $ 850 million. <PERSON> Provant </PERSON> said his agency believes the Sept. 15 date is `` arbitrary,'' and that it might be possible to have some crews continue working in the sound until Oct. 1. `` We would like to see that they still maintain come capability to continue working as long as the weather is nice. Plans to have everything out of here by Sept. 15 just seems too rigid to us,'' Provant said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> DEC </ORGANIZATION> plans winter activities such as overflights, mapping, beach monitoring and collection of water quality data. But <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON> said that was out of the question. `` We have no intention of doing that. We think it's a safety factor. We've never talked about operating in the winter on the cleanup,'' he said. The memo also said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s `` discussions with federal or state agencies is for the purpose of keeping them informed, and is not requesting approval. In discussions on these matters you should stress the safety and operational factors. We are willing to discuss these factors. We are not willing to discuss the decisions.'' <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON> said a shoreline assessment would be undertaken in the spring. `` We're saying we do not think that any cleanup operations will be needed because we plan to work on all the shorelines before we pull out,'' he said. `` There will be some oil that remains on some shorelines or down in the gravel. `` But we believe six months of winter storms and tidal action will remove most, if not all, of what's remaining,'' <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON> said. `` If there is remaining oil next spring it will be asphaltic in nature and it would be more environmentally damaging to remove it than to leave it there. It poses no environmental threat.''
