<HEAD>Expert: Literature Tests So Poorly Written They Encourage Shortcuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Standardized literature tests are so poorly written they encourage students to read condensed versions of classics, a study released Monday concluded. Multiple-choice exams are more apt to test students on memorized facts than on ideas, said the study by researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>. `` The reading of a poem is treated like reading an encyclopedia. What are the facts? It's the Joe Friday approach to education,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Purves </PERSON>, co-director of the university's Center for the Learning and Teaching of Literature. <PERSON> Purves </PERSON> recommended that standardized tests, like the Scholastic Aptitude Test for college-bound students, also use essay questions to make students think about what they've read. He said students can easily get by reading commercial plot summaries. Multiple choice tests satisfy school districts' needs for accountability without truly measuring competence, <PERSON> Purves </PERSON> said. `` They are n't particularly interested in how good the measurements of accountability are, just so they can have a number they can throw in front of their school board,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which produces the Scholastic Aptitude Test, has written multiple-choice test questions that measure analysis and interpretive abilities, spokeswoman <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Waanders </PERSON> said. `` It is true that there can be good multiple-choice questions about interpretation,'' <PERSON> Purves </PERSON> said. `` What we found was that there were very few of them on these tests.''
