<HEAD>Poll: Most Teens Take Up the Habit Because of Friends, Social Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most teen-agers who smoke do so because their friends light up or because they feel peer pressure, a survey conducted by teen-agers indicates. The poll, commissioned by a trade association of vending-machine operators, also indicates that teen-agers mostly buy cigarettes over the counter, not from machines. The poll results were released Monday, a day before the chief counsel for the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automatic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchandising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> was to testify before a congressional hearing on regulating tobacco sales through vending machines. `` We in the vending industry have long been aware that our machines are not a significant source of cigarettes for minors because the majority is located in bars, cocktail lounges and places of employment were teen-agers are not present,'' said the attorney, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Funk </PERSON>. The survey involved interviews of 1,015 people ages 13 to 17. The interviews were conducted at 40 shopping malls in 20 major cities. The study found that 42 percent of the teen-agers questioned started smoking because their friends used tobacco. Thirty percent said peer pressure was the cause. Association spokesman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said he could not distinguish between those responses, but said they are based on the respondents' words. An additional 15 percent of those surveyed cited smoking by parents or other relatives as the reason they started using tobacco. On the vending-machine issue, 78 percent of the teen-agers who `` often or occasionally'' buy cigarettes said they `` seldom or never'' used vending machines. Among teen-agers who buy over the counter, 43 percent said they get cigarettes at convenience stores, 29 percent from gas stations, 11 percent from grocery stores and 6 percent from drug stores. The rest said they got them other places. The poll was conducted by <ORGANIZATION> Response </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, which reported a margin of error of 3.2 percent. The company said it used teen-age interviewers in the belief that answers would be more frank than if adults did the polling.
