<HEAD>Inspector General Report: Energy Department Priorities May Not Be
Reliable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A $ 60 million federal attempt to detail environmental problems at nuclear weapons plants may not be reliable because <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> staff members did n't keep good notes, the department's inspector general reported Monday. The department said it disagreed with the IG's assessment. Aides who conducted the three-year survey of environmental problems at the plants produced poorly organized supporting documents, said the report by Inspector General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Layton </PERSON>. The supporting documents were mainly log books with notes taken in the field. `` They generally were not recorded in complete sentences and were not detailed enough to function as a memory aid even to team members, who may be involved in hundreds of findings at dozens of locations,'' the report said. `` The notes were neither indexed nor organized in a way that would allow anyone to trace facts or conclusions in the reports back to the source. Team members acknowledged that it would be difficult and time consuming to locate information in the backup documents.'' The $ 60 million inventory was ordered under Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. It was not immediately clear whether it will be used to set cleanup priorities for the highly contaminated nuclear weapons plants. <PERSON> Layton </PERSON> said the shortcomings in the way the plants were evaluated `` undermine the credibility of the process and call into question the usefulness of the surveys.'' Decision-makers `` can not be assured that the $ 60 million effort provides a sound basis for prioritizing environmental problems,'' <PERSON> Layton </PERSON> said in a memo to Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>. The Energy Department's response, included in the report, said the poorly organized records criticized by the inspector general were n't intended to be reference materials. The preliminary reports produced by the field staff were sent to the various plants, where they `` were not found to be deficient,'' the department said. <PERSON> Layton </PERSON> said there's a chance some contamination may not be adequately indentified, and there's a chance critical projects may lose limited cleanup money because they were n't put in the right place on the priority list. But the department said the inspector general `` extrapolated beyond what is reasonable.'' <PERSON> Layton </PERSON> briefly mentioned his findings during a congressional hearing last week, but details were not available until the report came off the press.
