<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decided Monday that the government must recognize conversions to <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION> by Reform and Conservative rabbis abroad, starting a new round in a controversy that has angered many American Jews. In another decision, a five-judge panel of the court upheld an Orthodox monopoly by rejecting an appeal that Reform rabbis be allowed to perform marriages in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The 4-1 ruling on the `` Who is a Jew'' question prompted leaders of the ultra-Orthodox Agudat <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> party to meet Monday night and discuss whether to to withdraw support from Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s coalition government. `` We have a secular court interfering in a religious subject,'' said Agudat legislator <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Porush </PERSON>. The party has five seats of the 120 seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Orthodox rabbis echoed Religious Affairs Minister <PERSON> Zevulun </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON>'s pledge to renew the campaign for a narrower definition of who is a Jew, <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` The problem remains as an open wound and will not be solved until it is solved at its roots: that a Jew is a Jew only according to Halacha,'' Chief Rabbi <PERSON> Avraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapira </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. Halacha is orthodox Jewish law. Interior Minister <PERSON> Arye </PERSON> <PERSON> Deri </PERSON> of Shas, an ultra-Orthodox party, said he would stop signing identity cards issued by his ministry. `` My signature means that information in the identity card is true,'' he said. `` If the court says I can not decide about that, I shall not sign.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said identity cards would carry a sticker saying data contained in the `` nationality'' and `` religion'' sections could not be verified. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, Rabbi <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoffie </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zionists </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> said: `` We're very pleased. What it means is that the law that currently exists ... will now be enforced.'' <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>, associate executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` At a time when there appears to be dissension and division, this is a welcome affirmation that the common bonds of Jewish history and fate have endured and continue to bind us into one people.'' The court ruling revives an argument over Orthodox efforts to amend <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Law of Return to limit those automatically entitled to Israeli citizenship. Orthodox Jews want to include only Jews born to Jewish mothers or converted according to Halacha, which in effect would mean by Orthodox rabbis. Current Israeli law also grants automatic citizenship to anyone who has converted to <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION> and is not a member of another faith. The change has been fought by Conservative and Reform rabbis, whose followers constitute a majority of more than 5 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews but who have few adherents in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. They say the Orthodox proposal would symbolically excommunicate them from Judaism and alienate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Rabbis in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> make about 11,000 conversions a year, while Orthodox rabbis perform about 1,000. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> favored appeals from eight <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> immigrants and one from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> who were denied Israeli citizenship by the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. The court's ruling said an Israeli Population Register Law of 1965 did not entitle the government to decide the validity of conversions outside the country. `` On this matter, it has no bearing on whether the community -LRB- conducting the conversion -RRB- is Orthodox, Conservative or Reform,'' the court said. The marriage ruling came on appeals made seven years ago by Rabbi <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> rabbi, <PERSON> Mordechai </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotem </PERSON>. The judges upheld three laws that give <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Orthodox rabbis exclusive rights to decide eligibility for presiding at marriages.
