<HEAD>Mosbacher Temporarily Suspends Enforcement On Turtle Devices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 7-10: ``In Galveston,'' with reaction of shrimpers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Commerce Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> on Monday temporarily suspended regulations requiring shrimpers to use new devices intended to protect endangered sea turtles from getting entangled and dying in their nets. <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>'s decision came on the heels of weekend protests by angry shrimpers who blocked ship channels along the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and threatened violence if the regulations were not changed or reversed on use of so-called turtle excluders. `` We have worked out what I think is a good compromise that indicates sympathy to the shrimpers and their families as well as caring about the endangered species in general and the <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> turtles in particular,'' <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> said after meeting with gulf state lawmakers <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> said enforcement of the turtle excluder regulations would be suspended for 45 days. At the end of the period, shrimpers would be required to pull their nets every 90 minutes but would not have to use the turtle excluders. According to lawmakers, turtles can live for 90 minutes underwater if trapped in a net. After the 45-day period is up, however, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> enforcement staff would issue warnings to shrimpers caught not pulling their nets after 90 minutes. The agency would re-evaluate the regulations next year. A study by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> is expected to be completed in February. In <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, hundreds of shrimpers awaiting word of <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>'s action at the <ORGANIZATION> Galveston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> station broke into cheers when they heard the news. `` This is a lot more than we though we'd get,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Santini </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>, who estimated he lost $ 6,000 to $ 7,000 during the ship channel blockade. `` We can make a living now.'' In <LOCATION> Cameron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, boat owner <PERSON> Ashful </PERSON> <PERSON> Authement </PERSON> said: `` If they go for 90 minutes, I can relate to that. But there are some times -LRB- when -RRB- it might take you that long to find a good fishing spot and then you have to stop and pick up.'' `` At the end of 45 days, it seems like we're facing the same thing again,'' said <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> deck hand <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. `` We got a good deal,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>. `` I think it is a reasonable compromise. It represents a sound way to approach the problem.'' But one environmental group planned to organize a national boycott of shrimp as a result of <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>'s action. `` The radical action of the secretary of commerce has convinced us that we need to take some radical action,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>, vice president of programs for the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>'s organization also planned to seek a temporary restraining order against <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>. The shrimpers had contended their business would be ruined by the turtle excluder regulations. In <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, on Monday, shrimpers met with representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGAN