<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Strikes Highlight Need to Overhaul Councils</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Speaking to...' with two grafs to move up reference
to Gorbachev saying republics should decide when to hold elections. Pick
up 5th pvs, `The Kremlin...' Minor editing thereafter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said Monday the strikes in Soviet coalfields were the biggest test of his four-year economic reforms _ worse than the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> disaster _ and he called for a shake-up of local councils often blamed for blocking progress. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> appealed last week for a `` renewal'' of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ranks from top to bottom, and his suggestion that local governing bodies also be transformed could mean sweeping leadership changes. Local elections scheduled in the spring throughout the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> involve multiple candidates and for the first time offer serious challenges to entrenched officials. Some members of the national legislature, the Supreme Soviet, said Monday the elections should be held earlier. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said each Soviet republic should decide when and how to hold the elections. He said party and government bodies as well as official trade unions should meet urgently to analyze the two-week strike that at its peak idled half the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s 1 million coal industry workers and deprived vital factories of fuel. The Kremlin chief told legislators almost all the miners have returned to work. `` We are coming out of a very serious crisis, the biggest test during the four years of perestroika,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. He said the test was even more severe than the April 1986 explosion and fire at the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant that killed 31 people, cost millions of dollars to clean up and sparked a nationwide environmental protection movement. The strikes dealt a serious blow to the economy, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said, but he reassured his countrymen that `` our perestroika will give results despite the tests we are undergoing.'' He blamed Coal Ministry and local officials rather than the miners, but warned, `` deciding such questions by striking will ruin our work.'' Communist maverick <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> Soviet that local party and government leaders have been inactive and insensitive to people's needs because `` they know they wo n't be re-elected.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said that because of the strike, governing councils should not wait for elections to make changes. `` Ripe questions require sessions without delay to discuss reports of regional executive committees, and where it is necessary to take personnel decisions, they must be taken without waiting for elections,'' he said. Several heads already have rolled, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> official news agency reported. It said the party chief and mayor of <PERSON> Stakhanov </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Donetsk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> `` were forced to leave their posts,'' apparently under pressure from strikers. One legislator suggested strike committees be absorbed into local governing councils because they proved they can get things done. In a meeting last Tuesday with party officials, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the party also needs `` a flow of fresh blood, and ... to be renewed at the level of the work place, the locality, the city, the region, the republic, the central committee and the Politburo.'' He said Monday that party bodies should analyze reasons for the strikes, which miners started to press for better supplies of food, consumer goods and housing as well as higher pay and better working conditions. He balked at calls for independent unions, suggesting instead the official unions `` think over what happened and what to do to make sure unions carry out their role.'' Deputies speaking at Monday's nationally broadcast session said the country needs better unions. `` We have to admit the trade unions do n't have the workers' faith,'' said Lithuanian deputy <PERSON> Kazimeras </PERSON> <PERSON> Uoka </PERSON> `` We have to give them the right to establish independent trade unions.'' Soviet unions act as djuncts of the government, handling distribution of benefits rather than fighting for workers' rights. Several deputies from mining regions also called for moving up local elections to this fall to give voters a chance to oust insensitive officials. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said such decisions should be taken in the 15 Soviet republics, not in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, even if it means election laws and schedules will vary. `` Shall we torpedo and limit this?'' he asked. `` We will hardly succeed, commanding from here.'' The Soviet president said at least half the 300,000 striking miners in the <LOCATION> Donetsk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>, the country's biggest coal-producing area, have returned to work. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said about 50 of the region's 121 mines remain idle. <LOCATION> Donetsk </LOCATION> strikers were among the last holdouts from a nationwide coal strike that started July 11 in western <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> and spread from the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Last week, the government granted concessions and Siberian miners returned to work. A strike leader in <LOCATION> Donetsk </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> 550 miles south of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, said by telephone that workers are awaiting `` decisive guarantees'' from the Supreme Soviet that the government will keep promises made to miners Saturday. The Supreme Soviet took no action Monday to guarantee the pact, instead juggling legislation to give priority to strike issues. A deputy from the <LOCATION> Pechora </LOCATION> coal basin in the Arctic told the Supreme Soviet that miners around the city of <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> remain on strike, partly because of media `` disinformation.'' Miner <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lushnikov </PERSON> said state media reported erroneously that the <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> strike had ended. Reports said miners remained on strike at 11 of 13 <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> mines and all 12 mines in <LOCATION> Chervonograd </LOCATION> in the western <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kucherenko </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said the strike settlements probably will cost between $ 4.6 billion and $ 8.6 billion.
