<SECOND>AM-Timber Compromise,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Unveil Compromise, Vermont Senator Skeptical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers unveiled draft legislation Monday to impose a ceasefire in the battle over logging in the ancient forests of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, but objections from a <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> senator sidetracked plans for immediate subcommittee action on the bill. Sens. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, R-Ore., and <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash., planned to ask the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to approve the legislation Tuesday despite concerns from Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt. <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, both at the beginning of the interior appropriations subcommittee meeting and in a letter to full <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-W.V. </LOCATION>, said he was `` deeply disturbed'' that provisions in the bill might preempt the right of environmentalists to appeal timber sales to <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>'s skepticism dampened the excitement of the bill's sponsors who hope to ensure an adequate supply of logs to keep the region's mills operating over the next 14 months, as well as protect some of the old-growth forests that are prime habitat for the northern spotted owl The bill calls for the sale of 10 billion board feet of timber off of the national forests and <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> lands in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> over the next 14 months. <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> said that is about 10 percent less than the amount of timber that would be sold if some sales were n't blocked by lawsuits to protect the spotted owl. In addition, the plan discourages logging significantly large blocks of old-growth forests, a policy known as `` minimum fragmentation.'' Under the proposal, significant stands of old-growth would have at least eight trees per acre that are at least 300 years old or are 40 inches in diameter. Environmentalists would be allowed to release 1.25 billion board feet of the almost 2 billion board feet of timber sales currently enjoined by federal courts in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. `` I am concerned that an appeal and judicial exemption process that started with isolated sales could expand to a region, and may soon become national in scope,'' said <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, who also is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which has jurisdiction over the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, who has close ties to environmental groups, said he was well aware that forest products were `` essential to the economic health'' of the region, but added the right of appeal was `` also of vital importance.'' <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> agreed to postpone consideration of the bill until the full committee meeting. The sales have been temporarily enjoined by pending lawsuits that claim over-logging in old-growth forests is threatening the northern spotted owl with extinction. The owl hunts and nests almost exclusively in ancient forests. The agreement would prohibit environmentalists from using injunctions to block timber sales in the next fiscal year, which starts Oct. 1.
