<HEAD>Forest Fires in Manitoba Force Evacuation of 18,000</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE and add details. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forest fires raging through northern <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> have forced the evacuation of more than 18,000 people, and smoke and flames threatened to block some escape routes. The airport in <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> was reopened Monday after radar equipment was flown in to help guide airplanes. Pilots were unable to locate the runways because of the dense smoke. Convoys of trucks loaded with food and fuel and escorted by police drove north from <LOCATION> Winnipeg </LOCATION> to reach <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> about 470 miles away. Some 4,000 evacuees were being sheltered in <LOCATION> Thompson </LOCATION>, a mining town with a normal population of 15,000. The fires were several miles away from <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and there was no immediate threat to the town. Just east of <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> firefighters sprayed water on a wooden bridge of a railroad used to move evacuees. `` If that bridge goes out then that escape route is cut off to <LOCATION> Churchill </LOCATION>,'' <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> Natural Resources Minister <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Enns </PERSON> told a news conference. <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> is a <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> port city 260 miles northeast of <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. The railroad also links <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> to the south. <PERSON> Enns </PERSON> said all available equipment was being used to evacuate people and to block flames from sweeping through communities. Officials said only a few houses have burned and they had no reports of injuries or deaths. Scores of fires have broken out in parched northern <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> in recent weeks, but winds fanned the blazes last week and they now form a belt more than 200 miles wide beginning about 240 miles north of <LOCATION> Winnipeg </LOCATION>. Evacuations started Thursday as flames threatened communities. Officials said fires in northern <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION> forced 1,200 residents of <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bay </PERSON> to flee their homes Saturday. They said that in northwestern <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, 400 people living at <LOCATION> Bearskin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> were flown out Thursday. The fires have swept through at least 2 million acres of brush and timber in a mainly flat area. Military transport planes, trains and private vehicles were being used to remove people from threatened towns in <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> in what is believed to be the largest evacuation in the province's history Officials said 13 towns have been completely evacuated since Thursday and a number of other towns were either partly evacuated or the residents were on standby. About 8,500 people were evacuated when floods ravaged <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> in 1950. <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> officials estimated there are about 250 fires in the fire belt, but they said the figures are uncertain. `` There is too much smoke; we ca n't even see the new fires,'' said <PERSON> Karin </PERSON> <PERSON> Batke </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION>'s natural resources department. <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> officials said at least 1,500 firefighters, 53 helicopters, 11 waterbombers, nine fixed-wing aircraft and heavy equipment including bulldozers have been thrown into the battle. A state of emergency was declared Sunday by <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Driedger </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION>'s minister of emergency measures. Retired or vacationing civil servants were asked to report for duty as exhausted relief workers toiled around the clock. `` Virtually all of northern <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION> is on fire, and we're just hoping some of our major centers are not going to be affected,'' <PERSON> Driedger </PERSON> said. `` Once you get 15 minutes out of <LOCATION> Winnipeg </LOCATION>, all you see is smoke.'' Lightning is blamed for most of the fires, but police believe people started at least two. Weather forecasts said there could be thundershowers in the areas, but the storms could cause more lightning-set fires.
