<HEAD>Judge Rejects State's Move to Block New Trial for Gary Dotson</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with prosecutor's comments, genetic tests,
other details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A circuit judge on Monday rejected efforts to block a new trial for a convicted rapist who is on parole and whose victim recanted her charges four years ago. <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> ruled that genetic test results obtained by <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>'s attorneys constitute important new evidence. He denied two motions by prosecutors to dismiss a petition for a new trial. Defense attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> said the ruling paves the way for a trial that will finally vindicate <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>. `` It's great,'' <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> said after the hearing. `` We're 90 percent there.'' But Assistant State's Attorney <PERSON> Gayle </PERSON> <PERSON> Shines </PERSON> said it was speculation to talk of a new trial. She said the state will outline its position at a hearing Aug. 14. At that point, <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> will schedule a hearing that likely will determine whether a new trial will take place. Ms. <PERSON> Shines </PERSON> said prosecutors have not decided what approach to take regarding the evidence that <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>'s attorneys say proves he did not rape <PERSON> Cathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>. <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> said genetic-test results prove that semen found on the underpants worn by Ms. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> the night in July 1977 when she said she was raped was not <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>'s. But Ms. <PERSON> Shines </PERSON> said the defense has failed to prove the test results have `` a substantial probability'' of changing the outcome of the original trial, a requirement for granting a new trial based on new evidence. And under state law, evidence of semen is not required to prove that a rape occurred, she said. `` Evidence that <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> was not the seminal donor can not by itself change the results of the trial,'' Ms. <PERSON> Shines </PERSON> said. She also argued that the statute of limitations on a bid for a new trial expired two years after <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>'s 1979 conviction on charges of rape and aggravated kidnapping. <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> rejected the argument, noting <PERSON> Breen </PERSON>'s petition contends that some evidence in the case was fraudulently concealed, which would override the law. <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> was not present, but a sister attended the hearing. `` We're going to prove once and for all that he did n't do it,'' said <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>, 26. <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> was sentenced to a 25 - to 50-year prison term after his conviction But in 1985, Ms. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> recanted her testimony. Now a <PERSON> Jaffrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, homemaker, she said she made up the attack because she feared she had become pregnant by her boyfriend. Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> granted <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> clemency, saying his punishment had been sufficient. But the governor said he did not believe Ms. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s about-face, and has refused to pardon <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>, 32, remains in an alcoholism treatment center as a condition of his parole last August. He had been returned to prison in December 1987 for a parole violation. Since his 1985 release, <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> has had recurring minor problems with the law, mostly driving violations. He also had faced two misdemeanor battery charges, one stemming from an altercation in a bar and the other prompted by an allegation of abuse from his wife. Both charges were dropped. <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> married shortly after his release. The couple have a daughter.
