<HEAD>Turkish Cypriots Release 82 Imprisoned Greek-Cypriot Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, CYPRUS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Turkish Cypriot government released early Tuesday all 82 <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cypriot </ORGANIZATION> women who were jailed six days ago for staging an anti-Turkish demonstration. Hundreds of Greek Cypriots, including President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>, welcomed the women at the police academy in the Greek Cypriot sector of the divided capital. Sobbing with relief the freed women sang the Greek national anthem to the cheers of the welcoming crowd. The women were driven to the academy in a convoy of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peace-force buses following their release from a prison in the Turkish-occupied zone of <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>. A total of 108 Greek Cypriots _ 98 women and 10 men _ were arrested Wednesday on the 15th anniversary of the Turkish invasion while demonstrating in the U.N.-buffer zone dividing the east Mediterranean island. They were charged with violating the border of the Turkish Cypriot state, which is recognized only by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. Sixteen girls, all under the age of 18, were released Sunday and Monday. The 10 men, including <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Chrysostomos </PERSON>, another Greek Orthodox priest, a doctor and two journalists, are still held. The release of the women followed mass demonstrations by Greek Cypriots and a 5-day sit-in blocking the main entrance to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters by hundreds of women. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> on Thursday called for the release of all of the prisoners. He also cricized both the Greek Cypriot demonstrators and the <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> police for entering the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> buffer zone. <PERSON> Eleni </PERSON> <PERSON> Vrahimi </PERSON>, a lawyer and one of the organizers of Wednesday's demonstration, said she and all of the other prisoners had been `` severely beaten'' by Turkish Cypriot police `` The trial before a Turkish Cypriot court was a mockery and a parody of justice,'' she said. `` There are no borders in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and we were protesting the Turkish occupation in the yards of a Greek Cypriot school and a church when the Turkish forces seized us.'' <PERSON> Vassilou </PERSON> told the crowd, `` The release of the women shows that humanity is not prepared to accept the violation of human rights.'' He expressed hope the 10 men would be freed soon. The conflict caused by the demonstration and arrests threatened to wreck the 11-month-old U.N.-sponsored peace talks between <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> and Turkish Cypriot leader <PERSON> Rauf </PERSON> <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> on reunification of the island. <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and seized 40 percent of its territory. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> said the troops were sent to protect the Turkish Cypriots who comprise 17 percent of the island's population. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> launched the invasion after a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking a union with <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>.
