<HEAD>Government Approves Program to Create New Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Cabinet on Monday approved a proposal by Finance Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> to allocate $ 137.5 million for a public works program designed to reduce the country's high unemployment. The decision came a day after about 1 million civil servants, bank employees and airport and factory workers walked off their jobs for two hours to protest the worsening job situation. <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s unemployment rate was 9.7 percent in May, the highest since a 1965-67 recession when the rate reached 12.4 percent. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said funds for the public works program would come from other areas and overall budget spending would not increase. He said he planned to cut $ 30 million from the budget of the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> and would trim other programs. `` I'm afraid of an increase in inflation and, therefore, we will see to it that the budget will not grow,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television. He said the plan would target `` development towns'' most affected by unemployment. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> began creating development towns in the 1950s to house Jewish immigrants, mostly from North African and <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> countries. `` The whole program stresses the development towns problems in at least three fields: Infrastructure of roads, water systems and schools,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Nissim </PERSON>, former finance minister, said the plan `` would not really help to ease unemployment,'' and he called for a more comprehensive economic plan.
