<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:WoodstockStore Adv30   07-24 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Woodstock Store, Adv 30,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 30 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Woodstock</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Peanut Butter Ran Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHEL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassmer </PERSON> ordered a shipment of <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION> key chains and cigarette lighters for their general store in plenty of time for any crowds this year. It's what they did n't order 20 years ago this summer that still causes a few pangs of regret. The shelves of their country store were nearly stripped bare that August 15-17 when about a half million youngsters camped out nearly two miles away at the <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION> music festival. For one long weekend Vassmer's, open since 1911 on the shores of <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> to serve residents of this 6,000-population town, operated like an exclusive nightclub. Bouncers stood at the front door and let customers in a few dozen at a time to shop. `` If I'd known, I would have had 50 cases of peanut butter up front and said, ` there you go, take all you want,''' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassmer </PERSON>. The Vassmers never made it up to <PERSON> Yasgur </PERSON>'s farm during the <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION> festival in 1969 when flower children frolicked in the mud and listened to The Who, <PERSON> Jimi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON>, <PERSON> Santana </PERSON> and others. They were too busy. But they could hear the music wafting through the air at all hours of the day and night. `` I did n't believe it would come off,'' <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassmer </PERSON> said, `` and I still do n't believe it was here.'' The Vassmers remember kids abandoning their cars in town late Thursday night, sitting on hoods and playing guitars and camping out in the streets and nearby fields at night. <PERSON> Vassmer </PERSON>'s, the closest store to the festival site, had n't even ordered any extra provisions. All of their canned goods were prized items, along with the peanut butter. Despite the crowds, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> said he does n't remember any shoplifters and none of the 25 checks he cashed bounced. `` They did n't bother anybody,'' <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> said. `` They were no problem. I'm sure a lot of them were on drugs, but they helped each other out. If one kid did n't have enough money, someone else would give him some.'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassmer </PERSON> said he dropped about 12 pounds over three days, mostly because he could n't bear to turn on his light and cook something in his apartment above the store with so many hungry kids on the street below. The couple love reminiscing about the festival with visitors, but they know enough not to bring up the name `` <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION>'' to longtime <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> residents. `` It's not a good topic for conversation because people who were against it, they still feel the same way they did then,'' said <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassmer </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> and the surrounding <LOCATION> Catskill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> region has let it be known they're not particularly sentimental for the 20th anniversary. <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> refused offers from promoters to be host to an anniversary concert, even when businessmen dangled enticements such as paying for a new town sewer system. Town officials are expecting several thousand people to show up at the former <PERSON> Yasgur </PERSON> farm for the anniversary. The concert was originally planned for the town of <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION>, about 50 miles away, but moved when promoters could n't get permission to hold it. At <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION> today, cynical store owners sell T-shirts with a map of the area making clear the festival took place in <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>, not in the famous arts colony. The Vassmers are part of a contingent of <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> residents who wish the town could cash in on its place in history by more actively seeking tourists, but anti-festival opinion has held sway. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassmer </PERSON> said some people still wander into the general store and recognize him from the movie `` <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION>,'' in which he was interviewed. Some even ask for autographs, which still leaves him tickled. His store, with the worn wooden floorboards, has n't changed much since 1969 Times have, though, and that's why he ca n't see a repeat performance of <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION>. `` Today you could n't do it,'' he said. `` It's a different attitude. These people were the peace people. They came up here for love and peace and music and that's what they got.''
</TEXT>
