<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 6</HEAD>
<HEAD>WILLOW CREEK, Alaska: in Alaska.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Imagine flying out over uncharted territory through narrow mountain passes in open cockpits with no maps, no weather reports, no radios, no landing strips, no places to refuel.'' Eskimos saw airplanes long before they saw automobiles and came to regard the pilots as paracletes. They brought medicine to the villages, fresh fruit, locations of caribou herds, news of relatives in other settlements. They took trappers into the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> and came back on appointed days to fetch them. They hauled miners and supplies to gold camps, hauled the sick to hospitals. A pilot named <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> hauled a cow from <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> so an ailing baby in <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> could have fresh milk. A pilot named <PERSON> Sig </PERSON> <PERSON> Wien </PERSON> hauled a chessboard on his 90-mile trips between Point Lay and <PERSON> Wainwright </PERSON> so two distant friends could have a game. By 1939, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s small airplanes and hearty pilots were hauling 23 times as many passengers per capita as the airlines of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 1,000 times as much freight. Empty wooden boxes labeled Stanavo Gas, each of which held two five-gallon cans of airplane fuel, littered the countryside. Stacked in outposts and trapper's cabins, they came to be known as <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> cupboards. On a stopover at Flat on the way to <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> found a Stanavo box in good shape and brought it back with him. `` If I do n't find things like this myself they might not be found,'' he said. `` We do n't have much help and the museum is practically broke. We're in a constant financial crisis.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON>, who is 71, was born in a mining camp at Flat, about eight miles from <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, and remembers when The Aviation reached there. `` It opened up a whole new era.'' He also remembers when <PERSON> Wiley </PERSON> <PERSON> Post </PERSON> crash-landed there in 1933 _ safely, but it was a close call. <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> videotaped <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON>'s recollection of the episode It was <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON> who told <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> about the abandoned remains of the plane at <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, how the pilot had salvaged the plane's engines after a crash and left the rest. The boxy fuselage, <PERSON> Miscovich </PERSON> said, had for a time served as a makeshift toolshed before it finally wound up in the gulch. <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> has in his museum files the history of very nearly every bush plane the pioneer airmen flew. `` I knew the Ptarmigan II was a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tri-Motor </ORGANIZATION>, probably the first in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. In fact, I had a picture of it, and of its pilot, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorbandt </PERSON>. `` Dorbandt bought it from an air service in the States which had named it West Wind II. It was built in 1928. <PERSON> Dorbandt </PERSON> bought it in 1934, brought it to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and renamed it Ptarmigan II. There never was a Ptarmigan I. `` Dorbandt was one of the really early pilots. He participated in the search for <ORGANIZATION> Eielson </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Eielson </ORGANIZATION>, at age 32, had crashed in a storm over <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. His fellow <PERSON> bush </PERSON> pilots mounted a search and one of them, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosson </PERSON>, found the wreckage and <ORGANIZATION> Eielson </ORGANIZATION>'s body weeks later. Soviet airmen had also joined in the search and a Soviet ship returned the body to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, wrapped in an American flag sewn from red and blue muslin and white ship canvas. Beginning with <ORGANIZATION> Eielson </ORGANIZATION>'s crash in 1930, fully two-thirds of the planes in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> were wrecked beyond repair over the next 10 years. Less serious crackups were commonplace. In fact, pilots came to expect some minor damage on every landing. `` But they persevered,'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> says. `` As a result we now have a fairly intricate network of air travel that unifies the whole state.'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> has arranged with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to fly out in a helicopter the first week in September and lift the remains of Ptarmigan II from the gulch at <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>. It will join its brothers in that panoply of history, each in flying condition, each with its own contribution to a storied era that opened up a hostile land. `` Ptarmigan II will have a place of honor,'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> says. `` It will fly again.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 6</NOTE>
