 `` Witchery'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Vidmark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>. VHS, $ 79.95. No rating. -RRB- `` Witchery'' is a simply terrible film with absolutely no redeeming virtues. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON>, who first horrified audiences as the possessed youngster in `` The Exorcist,'' and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasselhoff </PERSON> -LRB- TV's `` Night Rider'' -RRB- fail to save this piece of junk. Their lackluster acting, coupled with an impossibly bad script, should cause this video to gather dust on the store shelf. There is graphic violence and <PERSON> gore </PERSON>, including garroting, crucifixion, rape and other bits of murderous mayhem. But the story is so incredibly weak that even these excesses ca n't boost it to any interesting level. It has the look and feel of a made-for-TV movie, and is as dull as the worst sitcom. <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> plays an investigator of paranormal phenomena. She's appears half asleep most of the time, mumbling her way through her lines <PERSON> Hasselhoff </PERSON>, a photographer and <PERSON> Blair </PERSON>'s fiance, tries to make the best of it with dialogue about as snappy as a grapefruit commercial. The two have come to a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> island to take pictures of an old hotel that resembles a witch during certain times of the day. As the witch, <PERSON> Hildegard </PERSON> <PERSON> Knef </PERSON> is about the best thing going in the movie. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Manches </PERSON> plays the most credible role as <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON>, a child who communicates with the witch. _ By <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
