<HEAD>Star Watch: Get Serious</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Young Einstein'' opens Aug. 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You've got to take <ORGANIZATION> Yahoo </ORGANIZATION> seriously, after he has written, directed, produced and starred in a movie being released by a major film company. First of all, about his name. `` It's on my passport; it's been like that since I was at art school: <ORGANIZATION> Yahoo </ORGANIZATION> Serious,'' explains the 35-year-old Australian virtuoso who stars in `` Young <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>.'' `` I changed it to have an art work of a name but also make it a laugh. It kind of fit in with the rest of the stuff I did _ the weird hair, and weirder clothes and stuff. I had this really ordinary name -LRB- <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Pead </PERSON> -RRB- and I thought, ` I can do better than this.' `` ` <ORGANIZATION> Yahoo </ORGANIZATION>' is almost impossible to say unless you're having a good time. ` Serious,' I guess, is the director's side of me. I dunno. It's kind of a parody on names, I suppose.'' The other remarkable thing about Serious is the hair. It's a brown mass that rises from his head like a bramble <PERSON> bush </PERSON>. He calls it `` an Australian surfing haircut'' and claims it's the reason he chose to portray <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> _ `` he's the only historical character with the same haircut.'' Serious came here for his first exposure to the American media. He may well be the biggest Australian import since <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON>. His film, `` <PERSON> Young </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>,'' has broken records of `` Rambo,'' `` Star Wars'' and the like in his home country. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> is hoping, not without some nervousness, that Serious will catch on here. It's hard to describe `` Young <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>.'' You might call it a combination of rock music, silent-screen slapstick and bogus history. <ORGANIZATION> Yahoo </ORGANIZATION> plays <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> at the age of 26, when he discovered both relativity and rock' n' roll. All this happens in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, you see. The inspiration for `` Young <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>'' came during a trip down the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. He relates it with such sincerity that you want to believe him. `` I crossed the Andes with a mate, and we ended up on the border of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and I think <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. We were going to take a boat down the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION>. I do n't think they had Australians aboard before because we drank them out of beer in two days. `` We put in at a little village. The Brazilian native who was carrying the beer on board wore a T-shirt with a picture of <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> sticking his tongue out. Where he got the T-shirt in the middle of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle, I do n't know. That was the inspiration: The greatest mind of the 20th Century doing something so irreverent and childlike at the age of 72. I thought, wow, we've got the basis for a film here. Serious had dabbled in film before, making documentaries that somehow came out as comedies. How to sell a feature? He decided to do it by degrees. He sold his car, bought some film, borrowed a camera, gathered a cast and crew and began shooting. When he ran out of money, he borrowed an editing machine, put together what he had filmed and sought financing. Amazingly, he found backing from some investors, the <ORGANIZATION> Australian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, an Australian distributor _ and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros </ORGANIZATION>. He was able to finish `` <PERSON> Young </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>'' the way he wanted, `` with a cast of thousands and a huge musical score and eight rock songs.'' He was born in the <LOCATION> Hunter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>. He quit school to work as a tire fitter so he could afford to attend art school. It became apparent early on that he had to express himself not with brush and paint, but with the magic of comedy. `` I was fed by two of the major cultures, besides having the indigenous, sardonic, self-effacing Australian humor,'' he recalled. `` The <PERSON> Monty </PERSON> <PERSON> Python </PERSON> influence came on TV from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. At the same time there were all the wonderful'60s situation comedies from here, like ` Green Acres,' ` The Addams Family,' ` Get Smart' and all the others. Bugs Bunny was also a huge influence. `` At the same time, I loved epic films, especially <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lean </PERSON>'s. ` Lawrence of Arabia' was a huge influence on me. I loved the idea of putting comedy in a film of epic proportions. I had no idea it was going to be a big hit, that's all.'' <ORGANIZATION> Yahoo </ORGANIZATION> Serious is already a notable in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, and he'll certainly be the same here, with his electrocuted hair and his uniform of flowery Hawaiian shirt and floppy white shorts The recognition does n't bother him: `` I usually get ` G'dy, <ORGANIZATION> Yahoo </ORGANIZATION>,' ` G'dy, <ORGANIZATION> Yahoo </ORGANIZATION>,' that sort of stuff. Like I say, the word <ORGANIZATION> Yahoo </ORGANIZATION> makes people feel good.'' Can we expect `` Young <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> II''? `` Sequels are good when they are a small part of what is being made,'' he said. `` When they're the bulk of what's being made, I think it's self-defeating. Maybe when I'm a grey-haired old guy and we've forgotten about sequels, maybe we'll see ` <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> Goes to <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>' or something like that. But there wo n't be a sequel in the foreseeable future.''
