<HEAD>The Artists: In Love With a 20th-Century Modern</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's easy to pick out <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Nissman </PERSON> in a crowd of pianists: She's the one who's known for playing <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Prokofiev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginastera </PERSON>. `` What a joy to find composers in this century one can be passionate about!'' she says. `` Prokofiev is a 20th-century modern continuing the Romantic tradition. I believe the music cries out to be played that way.'' <PERSON> Nissman </PERSON>, whose parents were born in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, studied Russian language and literature at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>, as well as music. <PERSON> Ginastera </PERSON> visited the campus in the late 1960s when she was rehearsing his piano concerto and liked the way she played it. They kept in touch and, during the 15 years she pursued her career in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, she often played his music. The composer dedicated his `` Third Piano Sonata'' to her. `` I play all three. They're wonderful. I think the first is his masterpiece. My favorite of his works is ` Argentine Dances,' which he wrote for solo piano when he was 18,'' <PERSON> Nissman </PERSON> said. `` His widow, who's a cellist, and I are going to record the cello concerto he wrote for her. It never has been recorded. I think he would have been pleased.'' <PERSON> Nissman </PERSON> recorded all nine Prokofiev piano sonatas for Newport Classic, distributed on cassettes and compact discs by <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION>. Volume 2 was released in July with Volume 3 set for August. Last season she played all nine sonatas in three concerts at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Tully </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, the first time that has been done in one season. She repeated it at <ORGANIZATION> Wigmore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Next season she'll do the cycle in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities. `` There are plans for me to do the cycle in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> _ an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> of Russian origin going to play Russian music for Russians,'' said <PERSON> Nissman </PERSON>, who has been invited by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to go through <PERSON> Prokofiev </PERSON>'s piano sketches. `` They've done it with his symphonies, operas and ballets. Maybe I can find some manuscripts that have n't been discovered.'' Asked in a recent interview what led her to play the Prokofiev cycle, she said, `` Just following my nose, exploring music that is not often played in concert. I had played several of the sonatas with the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION>. I decided to look at the ones I did n't know. I was n't disappointed at all. `` I also found a fragment of a 10th sonata and a second version of the fifth,'' she said. `` I had the first page of the fragment and wrote the archives in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to see if there was a second page. It arrived an hour before the premiere was to be given and I sight-read it at the concert. `` It transformed my conception of the first page. He went in a completely different direction. It was very exciting to have that, to realize that at the end of his life he was going back to the lyrical style of the ninth sonata.'' That fragment of the 10th sonata was the last thing <PERSON> Prokofiev </PERSON> wrote before he died in 1953. `` It ends in the middle of a measure. He had a fall, but kept on writing on his deathbed.'' <PERSON> Nissman </PERSON> will make a Liszt recording this fall. `` I ca n't give up <PERSON> Liszt </PERSON>. He's one of my favorites,'' she says. `` They come from the same tradition. They all really knew and respected the piano and delighted in virtuosity, which is very appealing to the public and to a pianist. `` Prokofiev built on tradition with his own personality. That's the essence of what modern means _ being his own man yet building upon a foundation, using those elements to make it his own and have something personal to say `` People came to the recitals resisting <PERSON> Prokofiev </PERSON>,'' she said. `` The preconception is dissonance, that the music should be played without emotion, with a hard, dry, brittle sound. They were amazed at the lyricism and emotional content and what they felt when they were listening to the music. `` There is so much there. In his simplicity, <PERSON> Prokofiev </PERSON> is truly profound. I would say the essence of his music is the wonderful simplicity. He communicates directly. That's what one wants from any composer, to touch the soul.'' <PERSON> Nissman </PERSON> recalled that when she was a child and heard `` <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>,'' she was delighted with the melodies. `` And his piano music abounds with wonderful melodies. The fifth sonata is the weakest because of the lack of melody,'' she said. `` But the weakest for <PERSON> Prokofiev </PERSON> is still pretty darn good.''
