<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Eclectic English Band Finds Mainstream Acceptance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a summer dominated by `` classic rock'' radio, and concerts by reformed 1970s supergroups, Love and <ORGANIZATION> Rockets </ORGANIZATION> has managed to take its intriguing mix of dreamy mood music and jackhammer metal into the Top 20. While the members of the British trio express no love for oldies stations or the ubiquitous reunion tours, do n't count them among the bands complaining that a newer band ca n't make it in 1989. The band, currently on tour in support of its fourth album, `` Love and Rockets,'' has found a good outlet for its music on college radio. And concert crowds, which include fans of Love and <ORGANIZATION> Rockets </ORGANIZATION>' predecessor, the early'80s group Bauhaus, have been growing on the strength of the band's first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hit single, `` So Alive.'' `` We're over the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>, we are,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ash </PERSON> of the band's current success Ash plays bass, guitar, and saxophone and sings about half the band's songs. Rounding out Love and Rockets are the brother team of <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> on guitar, bass, harmonica and vocals, and drummer <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Haskins </PERSON>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> said each of the band's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tours has found audiences bigger and more knowledgeable of the group's work. `` The familiarity grows every time we come back. The songs are more recognizable to a greater part of the audience,'' he said. `` This is the most definitive record we've done so far. That's why we called it simply ` Love and Rockets.''' Defining the group's sound is an elusive task, as Love and Rockets works in a musical universe that has room for the latter-day psychedelia of `` The Teardrop Collector,'' as well as the noise explosion of `` No Big Deal.'' It's almost an axiom that the rise in popularity of `` classic rock'' radio, with its emphasis on'70s - style hard rock, has made it difficult for less established groups to get airplay or That phenomenon has been accompanied this summer by reunion tours by such veteran acts as The Who, the <ORGANIZATION> Doobie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Allman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Band </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Ash </PERSON> said that despite the attention to older rock music, in some ways the band has had better access to the airwaves here than back home in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Being heard on college radio has paved the way to increased mainstream acceptance, he said. `` I think the college radio situation in the <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> is excellent; it's a great idea,'' <PERSON> Ash </PERSON> said. `` With the college stations in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, they love playing their music and there is n't any commercial consideration They play what they actually like.'' The ideal radio station, <PERSON> Ash </PERSON> said, would play new records and also some good old music. `` Why not play something that was recorded in 1964, and then something that was recorded last Tuesday?'' he said. <PERSON> Ash </PERSON> said he felt strongly that rock' n' roll groups have a limited life span. He said he was opposed to the current wave of tours by veteran rockers. `` The Who should n't exist. It's stupid,'' <PERSON> Ash </PERSON> said. `` It's like a contradiction of what they were originally about. It's nonsense, it's a rip-off. `` They're too old to do that sort of music. When you sing songs like ` My Generation' and see guys in their mid-40s ... it's hilarious, it's wrong,'' <PERSON> Ash </PERSON> said `` When you're involved in something like contemporary music, it's real important to realize when you look ridiculous.'' He said Love and <ORGANIZATION> Rockets </ORGANIZATION> is just now hitting its prime. `` We just work on whatever feels right at the time,'' he said. `` We've grown close as a group. We can be open enough to know when somebody's doing something wrong.'' With its popularity growing, the band is recording some of its current tour dates for a possible live album. Also in the works is a home video compilation and mini-album of songs recorded around the time of `` Love and Rockets'' but which did not fit in with the sound of that album. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> described the mini-album as `` a cross between the Andrews Sisters, <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and Captain <PERSON> Beefheart </PERSON>.''
