<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Lopate Adv04-06   07-24 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Lopate, Adv 04-06,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 4-6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Individuals and Individual Voices</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON> prefers sitting behind a typewriter to standing atop a soapbox. He distrusts movements, getting caught up in any event larger than himself. A man of caution, he remembers with discomfort the 1960s group ritual of passing a body from one set of arms to another. What he does trust is the individual voice, expressed in writing through the personal essay. `` I think it's important because it's a direct conversation between the writer and the reader, and has the flavor of personality,'' said <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON>, author of `` Against Joie de Vivre'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Poseidon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, $ 18.95 -RRB-, a collection of personal essays. `` If you believe in individuals and individual voices, then it's one of the ways of getting a sense of dialogue going A personal essay gives you a model of a human being in all his hesitations and faults and confusions.'' His tales are more of observation than experience. <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON> examines the myth of <PERSON> Samson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Delilah </PERSON>, deconstructs the manners of dinner parties and, in the title essay, attacks mindless optimism. `` I think I have a streak of detachmant which is very suitable for being a writer and maybe not so suitable for other activities. It's very hard to knock me off course. I'm always watching in some way, some part of me refuses to be swept away,'' he said in an interview. `` When I write, I'm able to get a sense of perspective. So that experiences which are too painful for someone else to contemplate, I can think about with a certain humor, a certain wryness and begin to shape them.'' He is, admittedly, a believer in committing experiences to memory as they occur, even at the risk of reducing their emotional impact. Detachment is vital, he insists, a way of examining an issue to its fullest and working through to a well-considered conclusion. `` I tend to analyze and brood over what has happened to me until I make little stories,'' <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON> said. `` My essays have a strong story-telling impulse. Sometimes, they're really on the borderline between fiction and nonfiction; they're shaped in the narrative way. They're about characters, people as characters.'' <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON>, who worked as a writer-in-residence at a public school in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, uses this approach in `` Suicide of a Schoolteacher,'' examining the feelings brought on when a colleague takes his own life. `` When I write about something traumatic, I'm trying to overcome the pain and put it behind me,'' he said. `` Then I think I do n't have to write about it anymore, I've dealt with it But I also write to hold onto things that would otherwise be lost. It's a salvaging process.'' <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON> attended <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the early'60s, acquiring a passion for films that never subsided. He is currently on the selection committee of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> and credits movies with helping develop his skills at narration. `` Sometimes you learn an art by studying another art. I learned the grammar of film and it helped me to write. There's a great deal of cinematic influence in my writing. A lot of times, the scene will unroll as I'm experiencing it.'' In `` Chekhov for Children,'' <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON> describes the sometimes tortuous process of directing a dozen adolescents in the Russian playwright's bleak `` Uncle Vanya.'' He knows that detachment does n't work with children or the theater, and writes of the emotional highs and lows experienced during rehearsals. `` Children are always surprising,'' he said. `` I watch them and find them very dramatic. They do n't tone down their response so much. They'll tell you they hate you or love you; they do n't disguise very much `` That can be invigorating, and it can also be humiliating. If a kid does n't like you, it's more of a setback than if an adult does n't like you, because you feel they're responding very naturally.'' `` Against Joie de Vivre'' is <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON>'s seventh book. He has also published a previous collection of essays and an account of his public school experience, `` Being With Children,'' two volumes of poetry and two novels, including the well-received `` The Rug Merchant'' in 1987. <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON> views the world as a stage and himself a dispassionate critic, interpreting the actors' performances to the audience at large. `` Some writers are fascinated with language; I want to write beautifully and eloquently, but much more important is for me to capture character on the page _ starting with my own character and using that to spread outward, to use myself as a messenger that will bring back the world.'' He sees himself as fighting to maintain integrity in a world where people hide their real feelings. For <PERSON> Lopate </PERSON>, the personal essay is a written form of protest, a modern equivalent of burning his draft card. `` There's something almost subversive about the personal essay,'' he said. `` It empowers the individual. I also think that in a time when many writers are afraid to say explicitly what they think, as in fiction when they show but they do n't tell too much, the essay becomes a place where the writer testifies without a disguise of what she or he knows.''
</TEXT>
