<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 4-6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Bobby Vinton Still Singing About Love And Loneliness</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON>, still singing about love and loneliness 27 years after his first hit record, believes the title of his current album reflects his music: `` Timeless.'' <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON>, a trim and youthful looking 54, continues to turn out romantic ballads reminiscent of `` Roses Are Red'' _ his 1962 breakthrough song on the national record charts. The first single release from `` Timeless'' is `` Please Tell Her That I Said Hello,'' which is about a man crying over an old lover. Other selections on the album include such love songs as `` Getting Used to Being Loved Again,'' and `` I Made Love -LRB- With You Tonight -RRB-.'' `` I feel my music is timeless,'' <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON>, nicknamed `` the Polish prince,'' said in an interview. `` ` Roses Are Red' and ` Blue Velvet' still sound good today, and you can relate to them There will always be that type of music. There will always be a love singer, a singer of stories and simplicity.'' He's been flirting with a country, downhome feel to his music for the past few years. He uses fiddles and steel guitars on `` Timeless'' and is trying to get country music radio stations interested in his music so that he can be heard on the same outlets that feature <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Strait </PERSON>. `` I could be the beginning of the next dimension in country music,'' <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON> said. `` The country music DJs today are the old pop DJs of the'60s. We've all made the changes together. `` Country music is expanding. Radio stations are finding that if you play a <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON> type of artist, you can pick up listeners from adult contemporary stations who are getting too rock' n' rollish `` Country music is becoming the pop music of the'60s,'' he said. `` And that's where I came from. Country music is more than guys in a bar or guys in a corral. It's really growing.'' <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON> has sold 50 million records since `` Roses Are Red.'' His other hit records, mostly in the mid-1960s, include `` Blue Velvet,'' `` There I've Said It Again,'' `` Mr. <PERSON> Lonely </PERSON>,'' `` Blue on Blue,'' `` I Love How You Love Me,'' `` Sealed With a Kiss,'' `` Everyday of My Life'' and finally, in 1974, `` My Melody of Love.'' His memories of three of his biggest hits: _ `` Roses Are Red'': `` came out around graduation time and it was a great farewell song.'' _ `` Blue Velvet'': `` was recorded with 10 minutes left on the recording session. I did n't pick it and did n't like it.'' _ `` Mr. Lonely'': `` related to lonely people. There's loneliness in all of us and I felt it; I dug back in my soul for this and people felt the loneliness.'' He said he did well with love songs because he believed in their message and their emotion. `` I really feel them. I do n't feel rock' n' roll. You feel what you have inside and I have a lot of this. You ca n't fake it. I had an honesty about the records.'' He did as well in his own romantic life as he did singing about it. He's been married to his wife, his only one, for 27 years. His `` There I've Said It Again'' in 1964 holds the distinction in pop music of being the last No. 1 record before the Beatles led the `` British invasion'' of English bands who changed the sound of rock' n' roll music. <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON> was able to maintain a career, but many of his peers were never as popular again. `` They eliminated my competition,'' <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON> said about the effect the Beatles had on male vocalists of his style. A whole new generation of record buyers is alive now and <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON> is still competing for their dollars. `` I lasted because I made the right songs _ good, honest, emotional records. I do shows and give them a show they ca n't resist So they come back year after year and see me. I've changed my show to make it fresh, make it different. `` My music is part of a lot of their lives,'' he said. `` It brings back memories: their youth, their first date, their marriage. So they want to go out and enjoy their early life and growing up and all of that.'' He feels that he's a much better performer than he was 20 years ago. `` I was awful then. I was young, inexperienced, nervous and I was n't the confident performer I am today. Luckily, I was able to stick around to the point where I can walk on stage today and have control of the audience. `` Being an entertainer is like being a surgeon,'' said <PERSON> Vinton </PERSON>. `` The longer you do it, the better you get at it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug 4-6</NOTE>
