<HEAD>For release Thursday, July 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congress Moves to Add Barriers to Bias After High Court Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A little-noticed <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling making it easier for employers to limit older workers' fringe benefits has spurred members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to seek age-discrimination barriers many thought had been in place for decades. Lawmakers and advocates for the elderly are pushing legislation to nullify the June 23 ruling that bias in benefits such as health and retirement plans is not automatically banned under the 1967 Age Discrimination in Employment Act. In the wake of the ruling, `` employers are probably going to start tightening up'' on what fringes they offer to older workers, said <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottlich </PERSON>, an attorney with the National Senior Citizens Law Center. `` Employers may start rethinking how they're going to provide benefits.'' However, <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON>, whose <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> law firm, <PERSON> McGuiness </PERSON> and <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, represents management in employment cases, said companies are n't likely to make major cutbacks that would hurt worker morale. `` There's a labor shortage in a lot of areas. Instead of laying off people, they want to keep them. I'm not sure people would want to stay with an employer who said everyone over age 65 is going to lose benefits,'' <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> said. The government has long interpreted the age discrimination act as letting employers limit fringes for older workers only if it would cost more to offer them the same benefits given younger employees, for example life insurance. But the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> case, said the law bans biased benefit plans only in cases where the disparities are part of an intent to discriminate in `` some non-fringe-benefit aspect,'' of employment, such as hiring or firing. Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, in a strong dissent from the 7-2 majority decision, said the ruling `` immunizes virtually all employee benefit programs from liability'' under the age discrimination act. `` It is difficult to believe that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> ... intended to immunize acts of unabashed discrimination against older workers,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Horace </PERSON> <PERSON> Deets </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION>, said that while the ruling got little attention amid the excitement over long-awaited court decisions on abortion and flag-burning, it was `` an absolute shocker'' to the aging community. `` For years the assumption has been that benefits are covered under the age discrminiation act, as would be hiring and firing,'' <PERSON> Deets </PERSON> said. `` This puts older workers at a distinct disadvantage.'' The decision came in a lawsuit filed by <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Betts </PERSON>, who began working in 1978 as a speech pathologist at the <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retardation </ORGANIZATION> and Developmental Disabilites. When her work deteriorated, due to Alzheimer's disease, the 61-year-old Ms. <PERSON> Betts </PERSON> in 1985 was given the choice of unpaid medical leave or retiring with a standard pension of $ 158.50 a month. Because she was over 60, she was denied a third option of disability retirement with benefits of $ 355 a month. Lower courts upheld Ms. <PERSON> Betts </PERSON>' contention that it was a violation of the act to deny disability benefits solely because of her age, but the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had `` left the employee benefit battle for another day'' when it enacted the anti-discrimination law in 1967. The <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which enforces the age discrimination act, filed a brief supporting Ms. <PERSON> Betts </PERSON> and stating its belief that the law required `` some sort of cost justification in order to permit an employer to avoid a charge of discrimination.'' The court's ruling to the contrary is under review, and its impact on cases pending has not been determined, said <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>. The ruling's biggest impact will be in disability and severance benefits, which sometimes are designed to convert to pensions at a certain age or after a specified time, according to <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> of Towers, <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> consulting firm that often represents employers. But most employers already are accustomed to applying the act to benefit plans and are unlikely to make big changes because of the Betts ruling, <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said. Any after-effects of the ruling could well be short-lived, given widespread interest on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> in obviating it. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION>, has introduced legislation to extend age discrimination barriers to fringe benefits, and Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, also is considering legislative options. In the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Roybal </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION>, said he would introduce legislation `` We in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can not allow older workers to go unprotected in such a critical part of the employment relationship as employee benefit plans.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 27</NOTE>
