<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Life'sPrime:SunSense Adv27   07-24 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Life's Prime: Sun Sense, Adv 27,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, July 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix keyword line</HEAD>
<HEAD>Old or Young: Beware the Summer Sun</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a geriatrics physician, is director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION>, one of the 13 institutes that comprise the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By Dr. T. Franklin Williams</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The message today is simple: BEWARE THE SUMMER SUN! Too many people, especially older people, become needlessly ill because they fail to recognize the potential dangers of the sun and its heat. However, the two great dangers, heatstroke and skin cancer, are largely preventable. Symptoms of heatstroke occur almost instantly and can be immediately fatal, while skin cancer develops years after exposure to the sun's rays. If you must be exposed to the heat, drink plenty of water or fruit and vegetable juice, even if you are n't thirsty. Avoid alcohol and caffeine. Dress in light-weight, light-colored, loose clothes. Limit activity in the hottest part of the day and keep meals simple and light. If they are available, use air conditioners liberally. Trips to cool places are good alternatives. If you are a relative, friend, or neighbor of a person who is unable to get around you may want to offer transportation. Older people are especially vulnerable to heat-related illnesses. Changes in the body that may affect ability to cope with heat include inefficient sweat glands, poor circulation and changes in the skin. Also, some older people have illnesses that cause weakness or fever which, in turn, affect their ability to cope with heat. Heart, lung, and kidney diseases are good examples. Diseases requiring special diets also may make a person more vulnerable to heatstroke. People with high blood pressure, for example, reduce the amount of salt in their diets. Yet this reduction may increase the risk of heat stress. -LRB- A word of caution _ salt should not be increased nor salt supplements taken without consent from a physician. -RRB- Medications like diuretics, sedatives, tranquilizers and certain heart and blood-pressure drugs may contribute to a body's inability to regulate internal temperature. But never stop medication or change a recommended diet without consulting a doctor. Unusually heavy or underweight people also are at risk, as are those who drink alcoholic beverages regularly. Anyone suspected of suffering a heat-related illness should receive attention. Victims of heatstroke exhibit a body temperature of 104 degrees or higher. The pulse may be rapid. Other symptoms include flushed skin, a faint feeling, confused and bizarre behavior and combativeness. These symptoms require immediate emergency medical assistance. Heat fatigue and heat exhaustion are milder forms of heat stress. Should you suspect either illness look for giddiness, nausea, profuse sweating, and a cold and clammy feeling and take steps to prevent the condition from worsening. First, and perhaps most obvious, the person needs to get out of the sun and into a cool, preferably air-conditioned place. Encourage sponging off with cool water or taking a cool bath or shower and non-alcoholic, non-caffeinated drink. Another serious danger associated with the sun and aging is skin cancer. Whether you are 15 or 50 your skin is accumulating sun damage, including wrinkling, various growths and skin cancers and change in texture. By following some easy sun-safety tips many skin cancers can be prevented. Do n't sunbathe too long. Try to limit exposure between 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. and get used to the sun gradually. Wear a hat, long-sleeved shirt, and W-rated -LRB- ultraviolet -RRB- sunglasses. Use sunscreens liberally and apply them at least one hour before going out. Reapply after swimming or sweating. Sunscreens are effective at SPF -LRB- sun protection factor -RRB- 15. Prolonged exposure to the sun can cause skin cancer. The most common forms are basal cell carcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma and malignant melanoma. Basal cell carcinomas are the most common and rarely harmful to vital organs. Squamous cell carcinomas are less common but are potentially harmful because they can grow quickly and spread to other organs. Malignant melanomas often look like dark, irregular moles. They can be deadly. If you suspect skin cancer see a doctor. Warning signs include a new mole-type spot or changes in color, size, shape or texture of an existing one. With early detection and prompt treatment, many skin cancers can be cured. Even if you have had a benign cancer you must guard against the dangers of the sun. With good, sound judgment and a knowledge of preventive measures the hot summer months can be safe and fun for everyone.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
