<HEAD>Mom-and-Pop Research Company Builds A Better Safety Cap </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM LACEKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Kids do n't think like grownups. With that simple premise and a $ 50,000 grant from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, a mom-and-pop research company has come up with a child-proof cap it hopes will make life easier for older Americans. The caps designed by <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> do n't rely on an adult's strength or dexterity. Instead, they require two cognitive skills that children aged 3 to 5 do n't have: Read the directions, then do some things in a specified sequence, such as push, twist, THEN pull. The designs `` were similar to simple combination locks,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>. The Hunters recruited 26 adults, aged 60 to 75, from the <ORGANIZATION> Bozeman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, and 20 3 - to 5-year-olds from the <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a preschool associated with <ORGANIZATION> Montana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, to test three cap designs `` It was a much smaller group than you'd need to come to definite conclusions, but two of the designs were virtually child-proof. No children opened them. One child almost 5 -LCB- opened one of the designs,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said. The children seemed familiar with the now-commonplace safety caps, but were thwarted by the sequence requirements, she said. Ninety percent of the adults opened the caps and 80 percent rated them easy or very easy to use. A recent Gallup Poll of older Americans found that the No. 1 problem of daily life was opening medicine, the Hunters said. Safety packaging is optional on prescription drugs, and many older people, especially arthritics, refuse it. One result, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, is that one of every six children poisoned by a prescription medicine each year has taken a grandparent's medication. The Consumer Product <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is considering a staff proposal to test packaging for medicines and toxic household chemicals on elderly people as well as the children it is meant to protect. People over 65 receive 25 percent of all prescriptions, but testing uses only 18 - to 45-year-olds, <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Owens-Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, a $ 3 billion-a-year packaging manufacturer, has asked to look at the Hunters' findings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Computerized Phone Program to Monitor Elderly Living Alone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN PACENTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A computer that makes up to 100 phone calls an hour can alleviate one of the fears of elderly people living alone _ being undiscovered for days after being stricken suddenly at home by illness. `` There is a large percentage of elderly that live alone with a pre-existing medical conditions and nobody to check on them,'' <LOCATION> Youngtown </LOCATION> Police Chief <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Branham </PERSON> said recently, announcing plans to install the system. The service _ R.U.O.K., coined by developer <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> for `` Are you OK?'' _ is being installed in the <LOCATION> Youngtown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> suburbs of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>. R.U.O.K. was first installed in <LOCATION> Osage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, in March 1988 and has been started in about 15 cities, including in <LOCATION> Gulfport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, in July. `` It's a real simple system,'' <PERSON> Branham </PERSON> said. `` A computer modem hooks to a telephone and calls the elderly person. If they do n't answer the phone, the computer re-logs the number and recalls it eight minutes later. If there is no answer, a computer sends a printout of the person's name and condition to a police dispatcher, who will send an officer. The computer dials up to 100 phones an hour and should be able to serve about 500 people. A person may have the computer call any number of times in a day, <PERSON> Branham </PERSON> said. `` Everyone will get at least one call every 24 hours.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who attended a news conference kicking off the <LOCATION> Gulfport </LOCATION> system, `` If a person can answer the phone, we assume he's OK enough to call for help. This program is aimed at those who ca n't answer. The cost varies. Phoenix-area civic groups raised $ 7,000 to start R.U.O.K.; <LOCATION> Gulfport </LOCATION> police came up with $ 3,600 for theirs.
</TEXT>
