<HEAD>Honeywell Announces Sweeping Plan To Enhance Shareholder Value</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs with one graf to UPDATE with stock price.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, Renier said ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the subject of intense takeover speculation for the past two weeks, today announced a major restructuring program that includes reducing its weapons business and cutting 4,000 jobs. The company said it also planned to repurchase up to 10 million shares of its common stock on the open market and to sell a `` substantial portion'' of its 50 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Yamatake-Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese controls maker. Analysts have valued that holding at nearly $ 1 billion. The sweeping program will result in a 65-cent increase in the <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s fourth-quarter dividend, to $ 2.75 a share, and could include a special cash dividend, said Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Renier </PERSON>. <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said he expected the restructuring to improve operating profits by about $ 150 million over the next 18 months. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> is the leading manufacturer of torpedoes for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and also supplies small, medium and large ammunition to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON> said. Wall Street greeted today's announcement with open arms. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> jumped $ 3.37 -LCB- to $ 88.87 -LCB- in active late-morning trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, following a delayed opening. <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said the reduction of <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s weapons business is part of a strategy begun in 1988 to `` concentrate on core controls businesses that principally serve commercial markets as well as the market for military and space controls.'' The reduction will `` proceed over time in a responsible manner that recognizes the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's interest in these businesses so as not to adversely affect national security interests, our government program obligations, or the value of these businesses to <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> shareholders,'' <PERSON> Renier </PERSON> said. The weapons business accounts for about 20 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s revenue. <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON>, a company spokeswoman, would not say whether a sale of the business is one of the options being considered. However, <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON> said negotiations to sell the company's stake in <ORGANIZATION> Yamatake-Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>, which is listed on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, will begin within a few days. She would not identify potential buyers. Japanese investors currently own half of the company, she said. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s restructuring program will include the elimination of 4,000 jobs worldwide over the next 18 months, including 300 corporate staff positions targeted in a previous announcement. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> currently employs about 78,000 workers. Many of the job cuts will be made through attrition, but layoffs will be necessary, <PERSON> Tunheim </PERSON> said. The company had announced last month that it would lay off 300 employees. Today's restructuring announcement follows speculation that <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> is a takeover target. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price has risen sharply in the last two weeks following published reports that <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was considering acquiring the company. The takeover rumors began after the company announced that it lost $ 435 million in fiscal 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>'s second-quarter profit jumped to $ 74.8 million, or $ 1.73 a share, from $ 31.6 million, or 75 cents a share, in 1988. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McManus </PERSON>, a securities analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said today's announcement could deter a takeover attempt, although it wo n't guarantee independence for <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>. `` They are trying to basically boost the stock price to make it more difficult for someone to take them over,'' <PERSON> McManus </PERSON> said. `` It will also alleviate some of the large shareholders who have been pounding on the door. They are doing the things they have to do to deter a takeover.''
