<HEAD>Aerospace Company Profit Up 10 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marietta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its second-quarter earnings rose 10 percent over last year, mainly due to increased production of the Titan IV rocket. The company said net income increased to $ 86.9 million, or $ 1.64 a share, from $ 81.4 million, or $ 1.53 a share, in the same period last year. Second-quarter sales totaled $ 1.43 billion, down from $ 1.44 billion in the 1988 quarter. Earnings for the first half of 1989 were $ 146 million, or $ 2.76 a share, on sales of $ 2.75 billion. That compared to a profit of $ 132 million, or $ 2.49 a share, on sales of $ 2.74 billion in the first six months of 1988. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Augustine </PERSON>, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Marietta </PERSON>'s chairman and chief executive officer, attributed the strong second quarter to increased production of the Titan IV launch rocket, which had its first successful flight in June.
