<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bjorn </PERSON> <PERSON> Borg </PERSON> said Monday he refused an offer of fresh capital to rescue his struggling fashion business built on earnings from his 10-year championship tennis career. <PERSON> Borg </PERSON>, 33, said he turned down $ 4.6 million to help <ORGANIZATION> Bjorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Borg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Design </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> because he was afraid of losing control of his companies. <PERSON> Borg </PERSON> said he was negotiating other financing to keep his business afloat. `` I remain committed to the business and am in the process of trying to reorganize the management and corporate structure of the group,'' <PERSON> Borg </PERSON> said in a statement. <ORGANIZATION> Bjorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Borg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Design </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> produces a line of designer fashions, fragrances, shoes and accessories, and has real estate interests in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lars </PERSON> <PERSON> Skarke </PERSON>, who has a 25 percent stake in <PERSON> Borg </PERSON>'s companies, said the group was facing a `` a shortage of liquidity which is forcing the closure of the group.'' The company needs an infusion of cash to meet orders and finance further expansion, <PERSON> Skarke </PERSON> was quoted as saying in the Aftonbladet daily. <PERSON> Borg </PERSON>, the five-time <ORGANIZATION> Wimbeldon </ORGANIZATION> champion who retired from professional tennis in 1983, has boasted of his hands-on management style, making major business decisions on his own. <PERSON> Borg </PERSON> turned down an offer of 30 million kronor, or $ 4.6 million, by the <ORGANIZATION> Mercurius-Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION> to buy into the holding company <ORGANIZATION> Bjorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Borg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>,