<HEAD>Bankers Trust Reports Flat Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported nearly flat second-quarter earnings Monday, reflecting an increase in the banking company's provision for credit losses and higher non-interest expenses Net income for the three months ended June 30 totaled $ 174.6 million, or $ 2.14 a share, compared with earnings of $ 174.1 million, or $ 2.18 per share, the same time last year. For the first six months of this year, <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> netted $ 338.9 million, or $ 4.16 a share, up 13 percent from $ 300.1 million, or $ 3.79 a share, in 1988. Chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said the company benefited from a 15 percent increase in non-interest revenue, to $ 531.2 million, primarily through trading activities. But he said those factors were offset mainly by an increase in Bankers Trust's credit-loss provision and non-interest expenses. The provision for credit losses for the second quarter totaled $ 65 million, compared with $ 5 million in last year's quarter. The provision included $ 25 million for refinancing the debt of Third World countries. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>'s allowance for credit losses was $ 1.306 billion, up slightly from $ 1.305 billion in 1988. Net charge-offs of refinancing the debt of developing countries were $ 55 million in the second quarter, including $ 42 million of <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>'s non-performing medium - and long-term loans to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, the company said Total non-interest expenses for the second quarter totaled $ 444.1 million, up 8 percent over a year ago.
