<HEAD>Ferruzzi Calls for Study of CBOT Operations</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> on Monday called for a study of <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> operations, in a followup of the soybean processor's criticism of the exchange's emergency order that required traders to reduce their holdings in soybean futures contracts. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and a member of <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>'s executive committee, said the emergency order illustrated that the exchange had failed to keep up with the global expansion of commodities trading. He said a study of the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> should look at its grain delivery system, regulations, market stability, committee structure and market trends. <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said such a study should be undertaken by a group made up of soybean farmers, processors and others with a stake in the soybean market. `` The agricultural market is becoming truly global in nature. More than ever, it requires a strong and predictable <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` As it stands now, it is open to question whether the market is serving that function.'' The Board of Trade on July 11 ordered <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> _ part of the Italian grain conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fianziaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION> _ and other major traders to liquidate contracts for July delivery or sale of millions of bushels of soybeans. That decision touched off wild swings in soybean prices and the exchange's action has been widely questioned by farm groups. <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> officials said the exchange was worried that soybean supplies were insufficient for meeting large holdings of contracts for July delivery of soybeans in the final days of trading in that contract. <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> was holding contracts for delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans in July. He said those holdings were built up because of concerns <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> might not be able to fill export orders because of the reduction in soybean supplies due to the 1988 drought. `` It is both incredible and unacceptable that a market with international authority and, indeed, global responsibility, can be in a crisis over 20 million bushels of beans,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> refused to comment on <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>'s call for the study. However, a CBOT spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity said the exchange conducts internal reviews on a regular basis. `` We have an entire department, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analysis </ORGANIZATION> and Planning, that reviews the market on a regular basis,'' said the spokesman. `` It adjusts contracts if they need adjusting.'' <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> said that despite the global nature of the soybean market, the number of participants had declined. `` With fewer but larger players, hedging needs of the major firms have increased dramatically,'' he said. `` Do the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s operating practices accommodate this changed market? <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> also said a study should look into whether options have reduced futures trading and increased price volatility. Futures are contracts for the delivery of a specified amount of a commodity, such as soybeans, at a future time for a specific price. Options give a speculator the option to buy or sell futures contracts at a specific price during a certain period of time. `` Options are the preferred instrument of many farmers,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. `` When they enter to an options agreement, it puts a floor on the price. But they are free to take a better price should it occur.''
