<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings fell 67 percent in the latest quarter in spite of an 8 percent increase in revenue, the computer and defense contracting company said. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Blumenthal </PERSON> attributed the sharp earnings drop to the expense of cutting inventories, pricing pressures from competitors, and the temporary suspension of its defense business by the Pentagon. Also, the rise in the dollar decreased the dollar value of sales made in foreign currencies. Net income was $ 53.6 million, or 17 cents a share, on revenue of $ 2.57 billion, for the April-to-June period, compared to $ 162.3 million, or 78 cents a share assuming full dilution, in the similar 1988 period. Revenue grew to $ 2.57 billion from $ 2.39 billion a year earlier. For the first half of this year, <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> recorded a loss of $ 25.1 million in contrast to a profit of $ 311.6 million, or $ 1.60 a share assuming full dilution, in the year-earlier period. Revenue for the first six months this year was $ 4.78 billion, up narrowly from $ 4.76 billion in 1988. Three former units of <ORGANIZATION> Sperry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> were temporarily suspended from bidding on <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> contracts from March 15 through June 23, 1989. The suspension stemmed from a federal investigation into government contract bidding procedures. Two former employees pleaded guilty to bribery and illegal political donations charges. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> said the incidents occurred before <PERSON> Sperry </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> merged and became known as <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, but agreed to institute a company ethics program when the contract bidding suspension came to an end. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> is rated the nation's 15th largest defense contractor and last year received $ 1.4 billion in contracts from the Pentagon.
