 <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday reported a slight drop in second-quarter earnings despite a 7 percent increase in sales. Second-quarter earnings were $ 186 million, or $ 1.33 per share, on sales of $ 2.28 billion, compared to earnings of $ 187 million, or $ 1.39 per share, on sales of $ 2.1 billion for the same period a year ago. Sales rose because of an increase in worldwide prices for ethylene glycol, but earnings were down due to an oversupply of polyethlylene, the company said. For the first six months of 1989, <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> reported net income of $ 387 million, or $ 2.76 a share, compared to $ 288 million, or $ 2.14 a share, in the first half of last year. Revenue during the first six months were $ 4.5 billion, up from $ 4 billion in 1988. Union Carbide said all of its industry segments reported second-quarter sales increases. The segments include chemicals and plastics, industrial gases and carbon products.
