<HEAD>Energy Prices Plunge as Demand Weakens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices declined sharply Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on indications that demand for crude oil products is declining while supplies remain high. On other markets, copper prices were sharply higher, grain and soybean futures fell, livestock and pork prices finished mixed and precious metals were up slightly. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 14 cents to 77 cents lower with the contract for delivery in September at $ 18.74 a barrel; heating oil was 1.47 cents to 1.96 cents lower with August at 49.70 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.31 cents to 1.39 cents lower with August at 53.16 cents a gallon. `` A lot of selling was caused by reduced concern over the availability of gas oil supplies out of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritterbusch </PERSON>, and analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Carson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The easing of the coal strike in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was expected to increase the availability of European energy products, analysts said. Gasoline prices plunged as demand for the fuel declines in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Analysts said demand dropped 2.5 percent in the first half of 1989. The market was also influenced by news that workers in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil field are calling off a work stoppage and expectations that Tuesday's <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> report on oil stocks will show increased supplies. Copper prices rose sharply on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>