<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices fell sharply Monday, resuming a downward pattern begun last week. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the September contract for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, dropped 77 cents to settle at $ 18.74 a barrel. The September contract fell 17 cents on Friday, the first trading day for that contract. The October contract lost 74 cents to $ 18.45 while subsequent months posted slightly smaller losses. Among refined products traded on the exchange, the September contract of unleaded gasoline slid 1.36 cents to 53.16 cents a gallon and heating oil for August delivery lost 1.70 cents to close at 49.59 a barrel. Contracts for gasoline and heating oil scheduled for delivery later in the year posted similar declines. Analysts said technical and other factors contributed to the market's decline. `` This weakness started coming into the market last week and we made new lows on Friday,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We expected a follow-through today.'' Reports of a possible end to the coal strike in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> also impacted prices, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` There is no longer a fear that the strike could spread to the oil sector of the -LRB- <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> -RRB- economy,'' <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is the world's largest oil producer. A report Monday in an industry trade publication also sug