<HEAD>Thrift Reports $225 Million Quarterly Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Goldome bank, the thrift institution in the midst of a major restructuring under new leadership, on Monday reported a record $ 225 million second-quarter loss. <ORGANIZATION> Goldome </ORGANIZATION> said changes in its investment portfolio, the sale of several business units, writedowns on non-performing assets and layoffs accounted for more than two-thirds of the loss. The rest came from continuing operations. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Goldome </ORGANIZATION> president and chief operating officer, said: `` Some losses are losses and some are investments. ... These losses will actually save the company in coming quarters.'' It was the seventh consecutive quarterly loss for the company, one of the nation's largest savings and loan institutions. <ORGANIZATION> Goldome </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 19.5 million in the second quarter a year ago. For the second quarter this year, net interest income was $ 22 million, compared to $ 50.7 million a year ago, primarily as a result of higher interest rates, the bank said. Operating expenses were $ 178 million, compared to $ 102 million last year. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, a former president of <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said in April when he took over as head of <ORGANIZATION> Goldome </ORGANIZATION> that he intended to turn the bank into a `` customer-driven organization.'' Goldome immediately began selling off divisions not related to the company's traditional mortgage markets and announced a plan to trim employment by 20 percent. As part of the restructuring, <ORGANIZATION> Goldome </ORGANIZATION> reported the sale of $ 1.4 billion of high-risk and junk bond investments at a cost of more than $ 55 million; the reduction of $ 48 million in real estate and non-accrual loans; and layoffs and a hiring freeze that trimmed payroll costs by $ 19 million. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said the moves will `` serve as a platform for our return to profitability.'' <ORGANIZATION> Goldome </ORGANIZATION>, with $ 14 billion in assets, operates in two dozen states.
