<HEAD>Agreement Removes Obstacle to Growth but Does Not Guarantee Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to ADD quotes; Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Mexico's
agreement ...'; Names Rogelio Ramirez de la O. and Abel Beltran-del-Rio
cq. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Mexico-Debt Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The plan for reducing <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s foreign debt removes an obstacle to growth but does not guarantee recovery, economists said Monday. `` The benefits go beyond what you can see in terms of the reduction,'' said <PERSON> Nora </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustig </PERSON>, who teaches at the <ORGANIZATION> Colegio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, a graduate school and think tank, and is a visiting fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` It generates the impression to the world and investors who want to go to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> that the financial stability is more or less there,'' she said. Economists say elements still needed for recovery are confidence, lower interest rates, investment, domestic savings, reduction of the government deficit and continued containment of wages and price. They said that, even if those conditions are met, the government must be careful not to let the economy overheat and generate more inflation. `` The agreement will let the economy grow and will gradually raise our standard of living. It does n't permit dreams. But with work, we can return to sustained growth,'' <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> told a luncheon gathering of 500 of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s elite and powerful. President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> also spoke to the gathering attended by <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s most powerful business, industry, media, labor and farm leaders. In his remarks, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> said, `` every Mexican must now redouble his efforts'' but that those efforts can now be made with `` spirit, even happiness'' because they will result in progress. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s agreement in principle with a steering committee of 15 creditor banks was seen as a test of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration policy for reducing Third World debt and as a milestone for other debtor countries waiting to renegotiate. It represents the first significant reduction in a government's debt to commercial banks `` For the banks it is hard, but something they can live with,'' said <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. `` This really was a big reduction of assets for the banks, and this was a big matter for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in terms of how to get on top of the debt problem.'' Under the agreement, banks have three options: a 35 percent reduction in principle, reduction of the interest rate to 6 \ percent from the current average of about 10 percent, or providing new loans equal to 25 percent of what <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> owes the bank The deal applies to about $ 54 billion of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s foreign debt, which totals $ 107 billion, second in the developing world only to the $ 120 billion owed by <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. After more details are worked ut, which is expected to take a few weeks, the agreement will be sent to the more than 500 creditor banks for approval and choice of options. `` Is it enough so that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is in a relatively comfortable position to keep up with its payments? Definitely yes,'' said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Macro-Asesoria </LOCATION>, an economic consulting firm. He added, however, that savings provided by the agreement were not necessarily enough to achieve President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>'s goal of 6 percent annual economic growth by the end of his six-year term in 1994. `` That point is still to be seen because the external debt is the first step and probably the most important one,'' but those savings alone will not be enough to finance the growth, <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> had a net inflow of resources when its economy was growing, he said, but with the agreement, the country still will be sending out more foreign exchange than it gets. Officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> estimated the various options could save <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> about $ 1.5 billion annually of the $ 5 billion - $ 5.5 billion in interest on the $ 54 billion of commercial debt involved <PERSON> Rogelio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> de la O., a Mexican economic consultant, said the net transfer of funds abroad would be more than 4 percent of the gross domestic product even with the agreement. The government's goal was to reduce the amount from 7 percent to 2 percent. `` I am confident the agreement is going to boost optimism in the private sector,'' he said, but added: `` The Mexican crisis is not over.'' <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Beltran-del-Rio </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> CIEMEX-WEFA </ORGANIZATION>, an economic consulting firm in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, said the biggest risk was renewed inflation, `` The greatest risk is that it may generate growing pressure on public spending, which has fallen behind, especially in government-owned industries, and for salary increases,'' he said. <PERSON> Beltran-del-Rio </PERSON> said the government wage-price plan that brought inflation down from 159.2 percent in 1987 to an anticipated 20 percent 22 percent this year still will be needed.
