<HEAD>Paramount Abandons Hostile Bid After Delaware Court Rules In Time's
Favor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Under its ...,' to CLARIFY that Time not paying
for tendered shares directly but through an escrow account. Picks up 8th
graf, `When the ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> abandoned its $ 12.2 billion hostile bid for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday after the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld a lower court decision allowing Time to proceed with its $ 14 billion buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We find no error of law by the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION>,'' Justice <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Horsey </PERSON> announced as the three-judge panel unanimously sustained a ruling by Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, thereby affirming the rights of corporate directors to decide the future course of their companies. The decision ended <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s seven-week bid to acquire Time. Paramount issued a statement that it was dropping its $ 200 a share buyout offer but would continue trying to expand through acquisitions, mergers, joint ventures or partnerships. `` We believe in making bold moves when they are in the best interest of <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> shareholders,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. `` We have just demonstrated that in our offer for Time ...'' Paramount and several of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s biggest shareholders unsuccessfully had sought an injunction against <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, claiming that Time should be forced to consider <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s buyout offer. The tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> expired at 5 p.m. EDT and Time announced it held more than 117 million <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shares, or about 58 percent of the company's outstanding common stock. Time said it would announce Tuesday the exact number of shares tendered under its offer. Under its $ 70 a share offer, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> was to purchase slightly more than half of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s common stock and exchange a combination of cash and securities valued at $ 70 a share for the rest. Time said shareholders would start to be paid for the tendered shares on Monday. When their merger is complete _ a process expected to take several months the new <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, will be the world's largest communications concern Paramount said it would not pursue a bid for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s ruling gave corporate directors latitude in defending against unwanted takeover bids that they claim interfere with a company's long-term strategy. The judge said the proposed <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> deal, which was announced in March, three months before <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> launched its bid, was the result of long-term business planning and that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> and Time's shareholders could not interfere. Paramount has contended that once <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> announced its plan to merge with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> it effectively placed itself up for sale and under <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> law therefore had to consider <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s offer. During more than two hours of arguments before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantor </PERSON> said Time's board had a fiduciary duty to inquire into <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s initial $ 175 a share buyout offer. `` We do n't question that <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> is a good deal,'' <PERSON> Cantor </PERSON> said, but he contended Time shareholders should have had a chance to vote on whether <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s acquisition of the company would have been a better deal in the short term. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, an attorney for major <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders, including <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, said thousands of the company's stockholders opposed the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger. He argued that based on previous <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court rulings, the board was obligated to consider <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s offer. But Justice <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> G.T </PERSON>. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> interjected that <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>'s argument would make a board hostage `` to anyone who walked in with a bid,'' regardless of a company's long-range plans. <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said after the court ruled that the decision tilted <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> law in favor of management. He predicted attorneys would advise corporations to develop an `` appearance of a long-term plan'' to ward off potential takeover bids. When <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Joffe </PERSON> presented his case Monday, the justices asked why <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> _ which replaced an earlier stock-swap merger plan _ was not submitted to a vote by <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders at the company's annual meeting in June. <PERSON> Joffe </PERSON> said a vote was not required because the deal did not involve the issuing of new Time stock. Furthermore, he said, after Paramount announced its bid on June 6, the market for Time stock was in disarray and the price of the shares was seesawing. `` This was hardly the situation to have an unimpassioned evaluation of future value and get a fair vote,'' he said. <PERSON> Joffe </PERSON> contended Time's plans to merge with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> would give shareholders greater value in the long term than <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 200 a share offer. The case was heard in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> because all three companies _ like many of the biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations _ are incorporated there. Because so many major corporations subject to <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> laws, the Time case likely will have implications for other companies in the future. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> planned to issue a written decision at some point in the future. The justices' ruling was widely expected even before the hearing began. As arguments proceeded _ and were televised live by <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> _ Time's stock dropped on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Time stock closed down $ 1 at $ 137.50 a share. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> stock rose $ 1.62 -LCB- to $ 66.12 -LCB- a share and <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> rose $ 1.87 -LCB- to $ 59.37 -LCB- a share. Time stock, which traded at $ 126 a share before the Paramount bid, rose to a high of $ 182.75 before falling back in recent weeks as investors became increasingly pessimistic about the chances for Paramount's success.
